1
00:02:00,954 --> 00:02:03,498
Goodbye, sweetheart!

2
00:02:03,582 --> 00:02:05,667
T ake good care of yourself.

3
00:02:05,751 --> 00:02:07,211
Oh, Mummy, you forgot this.

4
00:02:07,252 --> 00:02:09,087
Angel!

5
00:02:11,590 --> 00:02:13,509
I worry so
about you living alone.

6
00:02:13,592 --> 00:02:17,012
Oh, Mother, it's adorable
of you to be so concerned,

7
00:02:17,095 --> 00:02:21,058
but I'm perfectly capable
of taking care of myself, dear.

8
00:02:24,353 --> 00:02:26,104
Come on, girls.

9
00:02:26,146 --> 00:02:28,398
Goodbye, my chicken.

10
00:02:37,407 --> 00:02:38,659
Yes, I'm free!

11
00:02:38,742 --> 00:02:40,202
I can live in New York
on my own.

12
00:02:40,285 --> 00:02:42,120
I can do whatever I want!

13
00:02:42,162 --> 00:02:43,288
Yay!

14
00:02:43,372 --> 00:02:44,748
Yes!

15
00:02:44,790 --> 00:02:46,834
<i>I was born and nurtured
in New York,</i>

16
00:02:46,917 --> 00:02:48,418
<i>the center of the universe.</i>

17
00:02:48,460 --> 00:02:51,755
<i>Unfortunately, my mother is
moving me to another planet.</i>

18
00:02:51,797 --> 00:02:53,173
<i>New Jersey.</i>

19
00:02:53,257 --> 00:02:55,634
<i>Is it any wonder
that I couldn't face reality?</i>

20
00:02:55,717 --> 00:02:57,427
<i>Can anyone blame me
for dreaming</i>

21
00:02:57,469 --> 00:03:00,430
<i>that she was leaving me behind
in my beloved city?</i>

22
00:03:00,472 --> 00:03:01,723
Mary!

23
00:03:01,807 --> 00:03:03,767
Mary, let's go!

24
00:03:03,851 --> 00:03:05,853
Goodbye, childhood home.

25
00:03:05,936 --> 00:03:09,731
Goodbye, intellectual
and spiritual stimulation.

26
00:03:09,815 --> 00:03:11,024
Goodbye, Broadway.

27
00:03:11,108 --> 00:03:12,109
Mary, please.

28
00:03:12,192 --> 00:03:14,319
Don't be such a drama queen.

29
00:03:14,403 --> 00:03:15,112
Lola!

30
00:03:15,153 --> 00:03:17,489
My name from
this day forward is Lola.

31
00:03:17,531 --> 00:03:20,784
I've known since I was 5 years
old that my true name is Lola.

32
00:03:20,826 --> 00:03:21,952
You were named Mary.

33
00:03:22,035 --> 00:03:24,121
It is the name
on your birth certificate.

34
00:03:24,204 --> 00:03:28,041
It is the name
that I am going to call you.

35
00:03:28,125 --> 00:03:32,004
<i>In my family, I am a flamingo
in a flock of pigeons.</i>

36
00:03:46,101 --> 00:03:47,644
<i>Goodbye, New York.</i>

37
00:03:47,728 --> 00:03:50,647
<i>Goodbye, any chance of becoming
a famous actress.</i>

38
00:04:10,334 --> 00:04:12,294
<i>Your parents tell you
to have hopes and dreams.</i>

39
00:04:12,377 --> 00:04:14,421
<i>And then they move you
to New Jersey.</i>

40
00:04:14,505 --> 00:04:16,173
<i>It makes no sense.</i>

41
00:04:17,424 --> 00:04:19,468
Welcome to Deadwood.

42
00:04:19,551 --> 00:04:22,221
Is she allowed to say that?

43
00:04:37,861 --> 00:04:39,363
Come on.

44
00:04:39,404 --> 00:04:40,614
Hurry, hurry.

45
00:04:40,697 --> 00:04:42,699
Let's see the new house.

46
00:04:42,783 --> 00:04:44,076
Come on.

47
00:04:48,580 --> 00:04:49,540
Oh, Mom.

48
00:04:49,581 --> 00:04:50,916
It's just grass.

49
00:04:50,958 --> 00:04:53,377
But it's all over the place.

50
00:04:56,380 --> 00:04:58,257
<i>The sun porch is my bedroom.</i>

51
00:04:58,340 --> 00:04:59,883
<i>Ordinariness
isn't the only thing</i>

52
00:04:59,925 --> 00:05:01,426
<i>I have to fight against
in my house.</i>

53
00:05:01,510 --> 00:05:03,929
<i>Gross injustice is another.</i>

54
00:05:03,971 --> 00:05:06,431
<i>The only person I can turn to
is Stu Wolff,</i>

55
00:05:06,515 --> 00:05:08,058
<i>the greatest poet
since Shakespeare</i>

56
00:05:08,141 --> 00:05:10,519
<i>and the lead singer
of Sidarthur.</i>

57
00:05:10,602 --> 00:05:13,730
<i>He'd see me through
my dark suburban days.</i>

58
00:05:15,440 --> 00:05:18,235
<i>In the city, I took two subways
and a bus to get to school.</i>

59
00:05:18,277 --> 00:05:20,237
<i>It amazes me
that I can get to school</i>

60
00:05:20,279 --> 00:05:22,406
<i>without it costing $1.50.</i>

61
00:05:32,249 --> 00:05:33,625
<i>Dellwood High.</i>

62
00:05:33,709 --> 00:05:37,129
<i>I shall be a bird in a cage
with a good school district.</i>

63
00:05:37,462 --> 00:05:39,923
<i>However, there is absolutely
no point in being negative</i>

64
00:05:40,007 --> 00:05:42,092
<i>about things
you just can't change.</i>

65
00:05:42,134 --> 00:05:44,428
<i>I look upon my new town
as an empty stage</i>

66
00:05:44,469 --> 00:05:46,805
<i>to which I'm allowed to bring
my own script.</i>

67
00:05:46,847 --> 00:05:49,641
<i>In my heart, I feel that
a legend is about to be born.</i>

68
00:05:49,725 --> 00:05:51,435
<i>That legend would be me.</i>

69
00:06:11,705 --> 00:06:12,456
Hello.

70
00:06:12,498 --> 00:06:13,832
Hey.

71
00:06:14,875 --> 00:06:16,668
I'm Lola Steppe.

72
00:06:16,710 --> 00:06:18,962
I'm from New York, originally.

73
00:06:19,004 --> 00:06:20,047
Ella Gerard.

74
00:06:20,130 --> 00:06:22,966
I'm from right here, originally.

75
00:06:23,008 --> 00:06:25,552
Well, hi.

76
00:06:26,512 --> 00:06:27,638
Hi.

77
00:06:30,641 --> 00:06:32,142
Hi!

78
00:06:33,352 --> 00:06:34,770
Hi.

79
00:06:35,854 --> 00:06:38,190
Have you ever seen
Sidarthur in person?

80
00:06:38,232 --> 00:06:39,983
No, but I think Stu Wolff

81
00:06:40,025 --> 00:06:42,277
is the greatest poet
since Shakespeare.

82
00:06:42,361 --> 00:06:43,487
I do, too.

83
00:06:43,570 --> 00:06:45,489
I have every CD they ever made.

84
00:06:45,531 --> 00:06:47,074
-You do?
-Yeah!

85
00:06:47,157 --> 00:06:48,700
And that's Stu Wolff dancing.

86
00:06:48,784 --> 00:06:50,911
I've downloaded
some great shots of him.

87
00:06:50,994 --> 00:06:52,454
Here he is at the Grammys.

88
00:06:52,538 --> 00:06:54,915
This is where he lives.

89
00:06:54,998 --> 00:06:58,460
This is the dress that I'm gonna
wear when we get married.

90
00:06:58,544 --> 00:07:00,087
This is him getting
into his limo.

91
00:07:00,170 --> 00:07:02,172
That black spot right there
is his head.

92
00:07:02,214 --> 00:07:03,882
What a wonderful
black spot it is.

93
00:07:03,966 --> 00:07:04,967
Hi.

94
00:07:05,050 --> 00:07:06,385
Carla Santini.

95
00:07:06,426 --> 00:07:08,095
Sidarthur.

96
00:07:08,178 --> 00:07:10,055
My father is Stu Wolff's lawyer.

97
00:07:10,097 --> 00:07:11,056
Really?

98
00:07:11,098 --> 00:07:14,393
Your dad must have been in the
same room as him and everything.

99
00:07:14,434 --> 00:07:16,186
Many times.

100
00:07:16,228 --> 00:07:18,814
Aren't you the girl who just
moved into the Swenska house?

101
00:07:18,897 --> 00:07:19,898
Well, I'm Lola Steppe.

102
00:07:19,982 --> 00:07:21,733
I didn't know our home
had a name.

103
00:07:21,775 --> 00:07:25,445
Is that supposed to be that
famous New York sense of humor?

104
00:07:26,572 --> 00:07:28,490
New Yorkers learn
to laugh at themselves

105
00:07:28,574 --> 00:07:31,785
and everything else
when they're very young.

106
00:07:31,869 --> 00:07:35,038
My parents took me to New York
for my birthday.

107
00:07:35,080 --> 00:07:37,833
I thought it was beautiful.
The lights and everything.

108
00:07:37,916 --> 00:07:40,544
I know why they call it
the greatest city in the world.

109
00:07:40,586 --> 00:07:42,796
Ella Gerard, you are
the sister of my soul!

110
00:07:42,880 --> 00:07:44,590
You should see Park Avenue
at Christmas.

111
00:07:44,673 --> 00:07:46,425
It's like walking
through the Milky Way.

112
00:07:46,466 --> 00:07:49,136
Except nobody gets mugged
in the Milky Way.

113
00:07:51,555 --> 00:07:53,932
We'll take our seats now.

114
00:07:55,767 --> 00:07:56,977
Miss Baggoli?

115
00:07:57,060 --> 00:07:57,728
Yes?

116
00:07:57,769 --> 00:08:00,689
We have a new girl
from New York City.

117
00:08:00,772 --> 00:08:02,482
We do.

118
00:08:02,566 --> 00:08:03,942
Miss Steppe.

119
00:08:03,984 --> 00:08:05,944
Miss Steppe.

120
00:08:06,028 --> 00:08:08,280
Miss Baggoli, I know it must
show on your records

121
00:08:08,363 --> 00:08:09,281
that my name is Mary,

122
00:08:09,364 --> 00:08:11,074
but everyone has referred
to me as Lola

123
00:08:11,116 --> 00:08:13,452
since I was a squealing infant
in my mother's arms.

124
00:08:13,535 --> 00:08:16,163
I don't even know
who this Mary is.

125
00:08:18,123 --> 00:08:19,082
I like that name.

126
00:08:19,166 --> 00:08:20,250
Lola.

127
00:08:20,292 --> 00:08:21,460
Lola.

128
00:08:21,543 --> 00:08:23,003
This is Lola.

129
00:08:23,629 --> 00:08:24,630
Lola, you should know

130
00:08:24,713 --> 00:08:27,382
that you're sitting in my
favorite seat in history class.

131
00:08:27,466 --> 00:08:28,675
I like to be dead center.

132
00:08:28,759 --> 00:08:32,221
Me too, and I didn't think
we had anything in common.

133
00:08:32,304 --> 00:08:33,639
I've earned the center seat.

134
00:08:33,722 --> 00:08:35,140
Besides, if you want to fit in,

135
00:08:35,182 --> 00:08:37,351
you probably shouldn't
draw attention to yourself.

136
00:08:37,434 --> 00:08:40,020
In case you haven't noticed,
I like the attention.

137
00:08:40,103 --> 00:08:41,939
Chill.

138
00:08:43,440 --> 00:08:46,360
Also, I wouldn't hang out
with Ella "Never Had a Fella."

139
00:08:46,443 --> 00:08:49,029
She doesn't really have your
potential, now, does she?

140
00:08:49,112 --> 00:08:49,821
Look at her.

141
00:08:49,905 --> 00:08:51,573
She dresses like
a politician's wife

142
00:08:51,657 --> 00:08:53,200
with the hair and the shoes.

143
00:08:53,283 --> 00:08:54,284
She's so random.

144
00:08:54,368 --> 00:08:56,912
And what about those glasses?
They are so 10 minutes ago.

145
00:08:56,995 --> 00:08:59,331
But I'm gonna stop myself
before I get nasty.

146
00:08:59,373 --> 00:09:01,500
I want to let you know
that if you're careful,

147
00:09:01,583 --> 00:09:03,335
you could be chilling with us.

148
00:09:03,377 --> 00:09:06,171
Chilling with you is what
I've always dreamed of.

149
00:09:09,007 --> 00:09:11,385
Hey, Ella, wait up!
Do you mind if I sit with you?

150
00:09:11,468 --> 00:09:13,011
Oh, no, that's fine.

151
00:09:13,095 --> 00:09:13,846
This is great.

152
00:09:13,929 --> 00:09:17,015
When you eat outside in
New York, your food gets dirty.

153
00:09:17,975 --> 00:09:20,394
So what's with
the Great Santini?

154
00:09:20,477 --> 00:09:22,062
She's beautiful.
She's popular.

155
00:09:22,145 --> 00:09:23,313
She's rich.

156
00:09:23,397 --> 00:09:25,732
In kindergarten, she used to
bite the heads off dolls.

157
00:09:25,816 --> 00:09:27,192
Ew.

158
00:09:29,152 --> 00:09:31,864
Who's that guy smiling at us?

159
00:09:32,364 --> 00:09:33,574
That's Sam.

160
00:09:34,324 --> 00:09:35,909
Sam!

161
00:09:38,370 --> 00:09:39,705
Sam, Lola.

162
00:09:39,788 --> 00:09:41,790
Lola, Sam.

163
00:09:41,874 --> 00:09:42,833
Hi.

164
00:09:42,875 --> 00:09:44,459
Hey.

165
00:09:44,543 --> 00:09:46,503
It's your first day here, right?

166
00:09:46,587 --> 00:09:48,172
Yeah.

167
00:09:48,213 --> 00:09:49,464
Well, it's good to meet you.

168
00:09:49,548 --> 00:09:51,383
You too.

169
00:09:51,425 --> 00:09:52,593
I'll see you later.

170
00:09:56,722 --> 00:09:58,807
<i>I couldn't possibly have
a boyfriend.</i>

171
00:09:58,891 --> 00:10:01,602
<i>I mean, I have to focus
on my acting career.</i>

172
00:10:04,229 --> 00:10:05,355
<i>After three weeks,</i>

173
00:10:05,439 --> 00:10:07,399
<i>I'm getting used to
the rich part of town.</i>

174
00:10:07,482 --> 00:10:10,485
<i>Gated, dull, Armani-ridden.</i>

175
00:10:10,569 --> 00:10:13,363
<i>You know, I'm the kind of
riffraff they try to keep out.</i>

176
00:10:43,560 --> 00:10:45,145
When Stu Wolff sings,

177
00:10:45,229 --> 00:10:48,857
"There's something in me
that always wants more.

178
00:10:48,941 --> 00:10:52,402
More moons and stars
and music in the wind,"

179
00:10:52,486 --> 00:10:54,780
it's as though
he's just talking to me.

180
00:10:54,821 --> 00:10:56,740
I like Steve.

181
00:10:57,741 --> 00:11:00,077
I bet Stu is hard
to get along with.

182
00:11:00,118 --> 00:11:01,954
You can tell he's sort of moody.

183
00:11:02,037 --> 00:11:03,372
Haunted.

184
00:11:03,455 --> 00:11:05,415
All true geniuses are haunted.

185
00:11:05,499 --> 00:11:07,793
It's part of what they have to
suffer for their art.

186
00:11:07,876 --> 00:11:10,128
Popovers, ladies.

187
00:11:10,963 --> 00:11:11,713
Wow.

188
00:11:11,797 --> 00:11:14,258
This is just like eating
in a diner. Thank you.

189
00:11:14,299 --> 00:11:16,468
Well, surely you have
popovers at home.

190
00:11:16,552 --> 00:11:19,012
I just popped them
in the microwave.

191
00:11:19,096 --> 00:11:21,265
My mother doesn't approve
of microwaves.

192
00:11:21,306 --> 00:11:23,475
She has very strong opinions.

193
00:11:23,559 --> 00:11:25,394
I've never heard
of anyone taking a stance

194
00:11:25,477 --> 00:11:27,604
on an appliance before.

195
00:11:32,484 --> 00:11:34,319
Why doesn't your mother like me?

196
00:11:34,403 --> 00:11:35,320
She likes you.

197
00:11:35,404 --> 00:11:37,489
She just thinks you're
a little strange.

198
00:11:37,573 --> 00:11:40,909
I mean, you are, a little.

199
00:11:42,828 --> 00:11:43,829
Lola!

200
00:11:43,871 --> 00:11:46,165
Lola, I'm sorry!

201
00:11:46,498 --> 00:11:48,959
It's really your mother
she thinks is strange.

202
00:11:49,001 --> 00:11:51,336
My mom saw your mother
in the supermarket

203
00:11:51,420 --> 00:11:53,589
wearing dirty overalls
with chopsticks in her hair

204
00:11:53,672 --> 00:11:56,008
and arguing with the butcher.

205
00:11:56,049 --> 00:11:57,843
It's not important.

206
00:11:57,885 --> 00:11:58,969
Not important?

207
00:11:59,052 --> 00:12:01,805
She's the woman
who gave me life.

208
00:12:01,847 --> 00:12:04,308
Whose milk fed my fragile body.

209
00:12:04,349 --> 00:12:06,643
Whose blood flows
through my veins.

210
00:12:06,685 --> 00:12:09,104
Of course it's important.

211
00:12:09,188 --> 00:12:11,481
My parents are square.

212
00:12:11,523 --> 00:12:13,400
Neither of them is too happy
about the fact

213
00:12:13,483 --> 00:12:17,654
that your mother has three
children and no husband.

214
00:12:17,696 --> 00:12:20,532
Single motherhood
is a transitory state.

215
00:12:20,574 --> 00:12:22,326
Karen used to be married.

216
00:12:22,367 --> 00:12:23,827
It could happen again.

217
00:12:23,869 --> 00:12:27,539
But I thought you said
you were a love child.

218
00:12:28,665 --> 00:12:30,834
Well, I was a love child.

219
00:12:30,876 --> 00:12:34,713
Mom and Dad were married
and passionately in love.

220
00:12:38,884 --> 00:12:42,346
My parents were mad for each
other as soon as their eyes met.

221
00:12:42,429 --> 00:12:44,014
Dad was like a rock star.

222
00:12:44,056 --> 00:12:45,682
Mom was a babe.

223
00:12:46,850 --> 00:12:49,019
The rest was destiny.

224
00:12:50,938 --> 00:12:52,689
They got married.

225
00:12:53,232 --> 00:12:56,527
And then they camped in the
desert and counted the stars.

226
00:12:56,568 --> 00:12:58,320
One million and three.

227
00:12:58,403 --> 00:12:59,530
One million and four.

228
00:12:59,613 --> 00:13:02,032
Jeez. My parents went
on a cruise to Bermuda,

229
00:13:02,074 --> 00:13:04,618
but they were afraid
to get off the boat.

230
00:13:05,160 --> 00:13:06,912
Mine were in love.

231
00:13:06,995 --> 00:13:08,956
Deeply, movingly.

232
00:13:09,039 --> 00:13:11,291
The only thing that could have
made their lives better

233
00:13:11,375 --> 00:13:13,085
was having me.

234
00:13:15,337 --> 00:13:16,338
Even as an infant

235
00:13:16,421 --> 00:13:20,217
I aspired to have a relationship
just like theirs.

236
00:13:20,259 --> 00:13:21,802
And then the twins
were conceived,

237
00:13:21,885 --> 00:13:24,304
and we couldn't have been
more thrilled.

238
00:13:25,180 --> 00:13:26,473
Upon hearing the news,

239
00:13:26,557 --> 00:13:28,642
my father mounted
his really cool motorcycle

240
00:13:28,725 --> 00:13:30,727
to buy the mother of his child
and future children

241
00:13:30,811 --> 00:13:32,980
her favorite flowers.

242
00:13:37,109 --> 00:13:38,485
Suddenly...

243
00:13:38,569 --> 00:13:39,736
Aah!

244
00:13:45,951 --> 00:13:49,329
They found him strewn
across 9th Avenue.

245
00:13:49,663 --> 00:13:51,665
And 10th.

246
00:13:55,335 --> 00:13:57,921
Lola, I'm so sorry.

247
00:13:58,005 --> 00:13:59,798
I had no idea.

248
00:13:59,840 --> 00:14:01,592
Ironic, isn't it?

249
00:14:02,926 --> 00:14:04,303
Your parents think my mother

250
00:14:04,344 --> 00:14:06,930
is the destroyer
of our social order.

251
00:14:07,014 --> 00:14:09,558
She's merely a victim of fate.

252
00:14:25,699 --> 00:14:26,742
What?

253
00:14:26,825 --> 00:14:27,618
Nothing.

254
00:14:27,659 --> 00:14:30,245
I like the chopsticks
in your hair.

255
00:14:47,095 --> 00:14:49,515
<i>Because Carla Santini
thinks she's Julia Roberts</i>

256
00:14:49,556 --> 00:14:51,975
<i>and the universe is interested
in everything she says,</i>

257
00:14:52,017 --> 00:14:53,352
<i>you can't help overhearing her.</i>

258
00:14:53,393 --> 00:14:56,522
So I had this really long talk
with Miss Baggoli yesterday

259
00:14:56,605 --> 00:14:58,815
about the drama club's
production of "Pygmalion."

260
00:14:58,857 --> 00:15:01,693
I told her I think it's really
rigid to stick to the original.

261
00:15:01,735 --> 00:15:03,529
Not stick to the original?

262
00:15:03,570 --> 00:15:06,657
Not stick to the exquisite words
of Mr. George Bernard Shaw?

263
00:15:06,698 --> 00:15:09,159
We're not English,
and this isn't the 19th century,

264
00:15:09,201 --> 00:15:12,412
so I think we should adapt the
classics to reflect our times.

265
00:15:12,496 --> 00:15:15,123
They're classics
because they're classic.

266
00:15:15,207 --> 00:15:16,416
Then I told her about my idea

267
00:15:16,500 --> 00:15:18,335
to move the location
to present-day New York

268
00:15:18,377 --> 00:15:19,962
and make Eliza a checkout girl.

269
00:15:20,045 --> 00:15:21,463
You're gonna be playing Eliza?

270
00:15:21,547 --> 00:15:22,464
Well, of course.

271
00:15:22,548 --> 00:15:23,924
I've already got the part.

272
00:15:24,466 --> 00:15:25,717
<i>When I moved to Deadwood,</i>

273
00:15:25,801 --> 00:15:28,178
<i>I really felt that a legend
was about to be born.</i>

274
00:15:28,220 --> 00:15:31,682
<i>Was Carla Santini going to
stand in the way of that birth?</i>

275
00:15:37,980 --> 00:15:39,523
Miss Baggoli, Miss Baggoli!

276
00:15:39,565 --> 00:15:41,942
I didn't know "Pygmalion"
had already been cast.

277
00:15:42,025 --> 00:15:44,361
I would have loved to be
Eliza Doolittle.

278
00:15:44,403 --> 00:15:46,405
Maybe if I could
just prove it to you now.

279
00:15:46,446 --> 00:15:47,531
Oh, no, no, Lola.

280
00:15:47,573 --> 00:15:49,616
I just put the notice up
on the board.

281
00:15:49,700 --> 00:15:52,703
Auditions are not until Friday.

282
00:15:53,787 --> 00:15:55,998
Thank you, Miss Baggoli.

283
00:15:57,708 --> 00:16:03,922
George Bernard Shaw
is a great playwright.

284
00:16:04,298 --> 00:16:08,760
And he's also a vegetarian.

285
00:16:08,802 --> 00:16:10,554
You're just in time, Lola.

286
00:16:10,596 --> 00:16:11,430
Quickly.

287
00:16:11,513 --> 00:16:17,644
I'm telling all the others
about this idea that I have had

288
00:16:17,728 --> 00:16:20,898
for our production
of "Pygmalion."

289
00:16:20,939 --> 00:16:23,942
Now, as you know,
"Pygmalion" is a play

290
00:16:23,984 --> 00:16:28,071
which takes place
in old-timey London.

291
00:16:28,155 --> 00:16:33,785
My idea is that we will set
our production of "Pygmalion"

292
00:16:33,869 --> 00:16:36,163
in modern-day New York.

293
00:16:36,246 --> 00:16:41,001
And Eliza will be a checkout
girl at a supermarket,

294
00:16:41,084 --> 00:16:46,423
And Professor Higgins will be
a professor at NYU.

295
00:16:46,465 --> 00:16:47,966
That is such a brilliant idea.

296
00:16:48,008 --> 00:16:50,010
That's gonna give
the play new resonance

297
00:16:50,093 --> 00:16:52,429
and immediacy for today.

298
00:16:52,471 --> 00:16:54,389
You mean it was your idea?

299
00:16:54,473 --> 00:16:57,518
Yes, Lola, it's my idea.

300
00:16:57,601 --> 00:17:01,730
I know I'm just a teacher,
but I am capable of thought.

301
00:17:02,648 --> 00:17:06,610
Now, since we're going hip
and modern,

302
00:17:06,693 --> 00:17:11,573
I have also added
contemporary songs.

303
00:17:11,657 --> 00:17:17,621
And I am calling it
"Eliza Rocks"!

304
00:17:18,664 --> 00:17:24,253
Now, each of you will be singing
a song for me of your choice,

305
00:17:24,336 --> 00:17:26,797
and then you'll be reading
a scene for me.

306
00:17:26,880 --> 00:17:28,966
But I haven't rehearsed
a song or anything.

307
00:17:29,007 --> 00:17:30,300
I'm simply not prepared.

308
00:17:30,342 --> 00:17:31,301
That's fine.

309
00:17:31,343 --> 00:17:32,845
You can just wing it.

310
00:17:32,886 --> 00:17:34,680
But acting is my chosen career.

311
00:17:34,721 --> 00:17:36,473
I mean,
I intend to be in theater.

312
00:17:36,515 --> 00:17:39,810
I don't want anyone remembering
a substandard audition.

313
00:17:39,852 --> 00:17:42,229
Then how are we to proceed?

314
00:17:43,188 --> 00:17:45,315
I guess I'll try, of course.

315
00:17:45,399 --> 00:17:46,942
Perhaps you could try now.

316
00:17:47,025 --> 00:17:49,152
You could go first.

317
00:17:51,321 --> 00:17:52,573
Okay.

318
00:17:54,116 --> 00:17:55,868
Take a spot on the stage.

319
00:17:55,909 --> 00:17:57,828
Anywhere you're comfortable.

320
00:18:01,832 --> 00:18:04,751
Maybe if we're lucky,
she'll fall.

321
00:18:06,336 --> 00:18:08,714
I'd like to sing a song
by my favorite band,

322
00:18:08,755 --> 00:18:09,965
Sidarthur.

323
00:20:12,045 --> 00:20:14,089
<i>Self-doubt didn't kick in
until the morning</i>

324
00:20:14,173 --> 00:20:17,134
<i>when I woke up with a heart as
cold and heavy as Mt. Everest.</i>

325
00:20:17,176 --> 00:20:19,636
<i>It was the day
the cast list went up.</i>

326
00:20:21,096 --> 00:20:23,515
<i>Why had I been so certain
I was going to get the lead?</i>

327
00:20:23,599 --> 00:20:26,059
<i>Miss Baggoli didn't say
anything encouraging.</i>

328
00:20:26,143 --> 00:20:28,228
<i>Carla smiled.</i>

329
00:20:38,572 --> 00:20:40,782
Well, look what the wind
blew in.

330
00:20:40,866 --> 00:20:42,117
Look what the cat dragged in.

331
00:20:42,201 --> 00:20:43,660
Ladies.

332
00:20:44,203 --> 00:20:45,162
After you.

333
00:20:45,204 --> 00:20:47,623
Right.
After me.

334
00:21:28,247 --> 00:21:29,873
Unh!

335
00:21:30,707 --> 00:21:32,251
Ow.

336
00:21:46,014 --> 00:21:48,934
Well, once again,
I got the part that I wanted.

337
00:21:49,017 --> 00:21:50,018
-Oh!
-Oh!

338
00:21:52,187 --> 00:21:55,732
There are no small parts,
only small actors.

339
00:21:55,816 --> 00:21:57,776
You can quote me.

340
00:22:03,156 --> 00:22:05,117
I'm your new Eliza!

341
00:22:05,159 --> 00:22:06,493
Aah!

342
00:22:06,952 --> 00:22:08,412
Amazing!

343
00:22:08,453 --> 00:22:10,080
I didn't think I'd get it,
but I did.

344
00:22:10,122 --> 00:22:12,332
I didn't think that,
because I knew you'd get it.

345
00:22:12,416 --> 00:22:13,876
No, 'cause I was...

346
00:22:15,002 --> 00:22:17,296
Actually, my part,
the one of Mrs. Higgins,

347
00:22:17,337 --> 00:22:20,257
is much more interesting
than Eliza's in many ways.

348
00:22:20,299 --> 00:22:23,051
I mean, even though
she's not the female lead,

349
00:22:23,135 --> 00:22:26,763
it's a part with depth
and true contemporary resonance.

350
00:22:26,805 --> 00:22:28,223
It's the one that I wanted.

351
00:22:28,307 --> 00:22:31,143
Good, 'cause that's
the one you got.

352
00:22:33,604 --> 00:22:35,898
I'll show you what it's like
to be in my school.

353
00:22:35,981 --> 00:22:36,899
Is that a threat?

354
00:22:36,982 --> 00:22:38,150
Absolutely.

355
00:22:48,452 --> 00:22:49,703
To "Eliza Rocks"!

356
00:22:49,786 --> 00:22:51,955
To "Eliza Rocks"!

357
00:22:52,664 --> 00:22:53,916
Oh, man.

358
00:22:53,999 --> 00:22:55,876
-Congratulations.
-This is the best day.

359
00:22:55,959 --> 00:22:58,795
I can't imagine that
Carla got beat out!

360
00:23:03,425 --> 00:23:06,178
Hey, Sidarthur
fans, how about some big news?

361
00:23:06,220 --> 00:23:07,387
You heard it here first.

362
00:23:07,471 --> 00:23:08,889
The band is breaking up.

363
00:23:08,972 --> 00:23:10,724
-What?
-Yep, Sidarthur is no more.

364
00:23:10,807 --> 00:23:12,476
I repeat, no more.

365
00:23:12,518 --> 00:23:14,019
Stu Wolff is moving on
and saying,

366
00:23:14,061 --> 00:23:16,104
"Never, never, will I work
with them again."

367
00:23:16,188 --> 00:23:17,856
So, in memory of the band,

368
00:23:17,940 --> 00:23:21,109
Iet's hear a track
from "Always Morning."

369
00:23:25,572 --> 00:23:26,532
No!

370
00:23:26,573 --> 00:23:27,574
It can't be!

371
00:23:27,658 --> 00:23:29,701
It just can't be!

372
00:23:29,785 --> 00:23:30,702
Aah! Aah! Aah!

373
00:23:30,786 --> 00:23:32,538
What?
What's the matter?

374
00:23:32,579 --> 00:23:35,040
I can't breathe.
Mom, I can't breathe.

375
00:23:43,590 --> 00:23:44,925
I heard.

376
00:23:45,008 --> 00:23:47,511
Thanks for being here
at a time like this.

377
00:23:54,101 --> 00:23:55,853
I don't want to believe it.

378
00:23:55,894 --> 00:24:00,148
I made these flyers to hand out
to fans urging them to protest.

379
00:24:01,441 --> 00:24:03,777
As these balloons
go to the heavens,

380
00:24:03,861 --> 00:24:05,988
so do the stars of our Sidarthur

381
00:24:06,071 --> 00:24:08,907
mix among the stars
of our universe.

382
00:24:12,161 --> 00:24:14,580
Symbolically, of course.

383
00:24:29,386 --> 00:24:30,345
Can you believe this?

384
00:24:30,429 --> 00:24:31,847
One of the most
catastrophic events

385
00:24:31,930 --> 00:24:33,932
in the history of the universe
has occurred,

386
00:24:34,016 --> 00:24:36,935
and everyone's acting
as if nothing has happened.

387
00:24:38,604 --> 00:24:40,189
Great.

388
00:24:40,272 --> 00:24:42,608
Me again, of course.

389
00:24:42,649 --> 00:24:43,942
So, who's next?

390
00:24:43,984 --> 00:24:45,068
Me.

391
00:24:45,110 --> 00:24:47,404
Are you crazy?
Carla's the all-time champion.

392
00:24:47,446 --> 00:24:50,073
So? There's gonna be
a new all-time champion.

393
00:24:53,118 --> 00:24:54,161
I think you've peaked.

394
00:24:54,244 --> 00:24:55,871
Hop on.

395
00:24:55,954 --> 00:24:58,081
Round one.

396
00:24:58,165 --> 00:25:01,376
My father, who, as you know,
is the lawyer for Sidarthur,

397
00:25:01,460 --> 00:25:04,087
just called me to tell me what
he found out about the band.

398
00:25:04,129 --> 00:25:05,464
Oh, really?

399
00:25:05,506 --> 00:25:08,091
What he told me isn't available
to the public yet.

400
00:25:08,133 --> 00:25:11,428
Sidarthur's having a farewell
concert in New York next month.

401
00:25:11,470 --> 00:25:14,765
Daddy already has V.I.P. seats,
but that's not the best part.

402
00:25:14,806 --> 00:25:16,642
I didn't think it would be.

403
00:25:19,645 --> 00:25:21,688
There's gonna be a party
afterwards at Stu's loft

404
00:25:21,772 --> 00:25:23,607
for all of Sidarthur's
closest friends.

405
00:25:23,649 --> 00:25:25,025
So I've heard.

406
00:25:25,108 --> 00:25:27,569
And guess who already
has an invitation?

407
00:25:29,321 --> 00:25:31,114
It just so happens
that Ella and I do.

408
00:25:31,156 --> 00:25:32,699
-Oh, really?
-Yeah, really.

409
00:25:32,783 --> 00:25:34,117
How'd you manage that?

410
00:25:34,159 --> 00:25:36,370
Same way you did.
Through parental connections.

411
00:25:36,453 --> 00:25:39,456
What connections do you have
other than the phone?

412
00:25:48,173 --> 00:25:49,299
Winner.

413
00:25:49,341 --> 00:25:50,384
Me again.

414
00:25:50,467 --> 00:25:51,510
Loser.

415
00:25:51,593 --> 00:25:52,636
Game's not over yet.

416
00:25:52,719 --> 00:25:54,555
Round two.

417
00:25:55,639 --> 00:25:58,892
Actually, my mother
has the connections.

418
00:25:58,976 --> 00:26:01,144
Marsh Warner bought a piece
from her last summer.

419
00:26:01,186 --> 00:26:03,188
And Marshie, as I call him,
is their manager.

420
00:26:03,230 --> 00:26:05,774
I know who he is.

421
00:26:06,358 --> 00:26:09,236
He remembered I was crazy about
Sidarthur, so he got us invited.

422
00:26:09,319 --> 00:26:12,322
Wow, your mom
must be some potter.

423
00:26:28,213 --> 00:26:30,007
Winner.

424
00:26:30,549 --> 00:26:31,800
Me, Lola Steppe.

425
00:26:31,884 --> 00:26:32,926
Remember that name.

426
00:26:33,010 --> 00:26:34,678
Loser.

427
00:26:34,720 --> 00:26:35,846
Awesome!

428
00:26:47,900 --> 00:26:50,986
Why did you tell Carla that
we were invited to his party?

429
00:26:51,069 --> 00:26:53,530
You would have done the exact
same thing if you were me.

430
00:26:53,572 --> 00:26:54,531
I wouldn't have lied.

431
00:26:54,573 --> 00:26:56,283
I would have thought
before I spoke.

432
00:26:56,366 --> 00:26:57,951
I can't even imagine being you.

433
00:26:58,035 --> 00:26:59,703
Carla Santini drives me insane.

434
00:26:59,745 --> 00:27:00,704
Don't even say that.

435
00:27:00,746 --> 00:27:02,664
Two of her nannies
were institutionalized.

436
00:27:02,748 --> 00:27:03,874
Not to worry.

437
00:27:03,957 --> 00:27:05,751
You just handed her
exactly what she needs

438
00:27:05,834 --> 00:27:07,377
to ridicule you
and humiliate you

439
00:27:07,461 --> 00:27:09,213
for the rest of your life,
and me, too!

440
00:27:09,254 --> 00:27:10,631
I guess it depends, doesn't it?

441
00:27:10,714 --> 00:27:11,882
Depends on what?

442
00:27:11,924 --> 00:27:13,467
Well, on whether we go.

443
00:27:13,550 --> 00:27:14,885
To the concert?

444
00:27:14,927 --> 00:27:15,886
In New York?

445
00:27:15,928 --> 00:27:17,513
And the party.

446
00:27:17,846 --> 00:27:20,098
We haven't exactly been invited.

447
00:27:20,182 --> 00:27:22,434
You don't have to be invited
to a party like that.

448
00:27:22,518 --> 00:27:24,645
There are people
in New York that don't go out

449
00:27:24,728 --> 00:27:27,105
unless it's to crash
a celebrity bash.

450
00:27:27,147 --> 00:27:28,815
My mother would never let me go.

451
00:27:28,899 --> 00:27:30,776
We can work around
your mother, Ella.

452
00:27:30,859 --> 00:27:33,654
Tell the truth.
Are you partially insane?

453
00:27:33,737 --> 00:27:35,948
You know, we have to go.

454
00:27:36,031 --> 00:27:38,158
It's a matter of pride.

455
00:27:43,205 --> 00:27:45,415
Is there something wrong
with the salmon?

456
00:27:45,457 --> 00:27:47,417
No, just not very hungry.

457
00:27:47,459 --> 00:27:48,418
In too much pain.

458
00:27:48,460 --> 00:27:50,921
I'm in pain, too.
My tooth's coming out.

459
00:27:50,963 --> 00:27:51,713
Oh!

460
00:27:51,797 --> 00:27:53,131
It's not that kind of pain.

461
00:27:53,215 --> 00:27:54,967
It's pain of the heart.

462
00:27:55,008 --> 00:27:56,718
Sidarthur's broken up.

463
00:27:56,802 --> 00:27:58,679
They're having one last concert
in New York.

464
00:27:58,762 --> 00:28:00,639
That's it.
They're done.

465
00:28:01,139 --> 00:28:02,724
Good night, sweet princes.

466
00:28:02,808 --> 00:28:05,686
May choirs of rock angels
sing you to sleep.

467
00:28:05,769 --> 00:28:07,437
I have no reason
to live without them.

468
00:28:07,521 --> 00:28:09,106
Let me take a wild guess.

469
00:28:09,147 --> 00:28:11,108
You want to go to the concert.

470
00:28:11,149 --> 00:28:13,151
If I could just see them
play live.

471
00:28:13,193 --> 00:28:14,862
I'd have the memory
to carry me through

472
00:28:14,945 --> 00:28:18,532
the long, empty years that lie
ahead, like a road in Kansas.

473
00:28:18,615 --> 00:28:21,201
Okay, I don't think
that kids and rock concerts

474
00:28:21,285 --> 00:28:22,828
are a great mix.

475
00:28:22,911 --> 00:28:24,288
How can you treat me like this?

476
00:28:24,329 --> 00:28:25,873
I was your firstborn.

477
00:28:25,956 --> 00:28:28,500
You leaned over my crib
to make sure I was breathing.

478
00:28:28,584 --> 00:28:30,627
That's why I want to
keep you alive.

479
00:28:30,711 --> 00:28:33,630
She wouldn't even stop for the
tiniest, most subatomic second

480
00:28:33,672 --> 00:28:35,549
to consider
my fragile hopes and dreams.

481
00:28:35,632 --> 00:28:37,092
What did Ella's mother say?

482
00:28:37,176 --> 00:28:38,260
She didn't ask her.

483
00:28:38,343 --> 00:28:40,679
She said her mom would
bite off a $10 acrylic nail

484
00:28:40,721 --> 00:28:42,306
if she even brought it up.

485
00:28:42,639 --> 00:28:45,434
So I guess that's that.

486
00:28:45,517 --> 00:28:49,396
No, I'm not exactly a
"que será, será" kind of person.

487
00:28:50,022 --> 00:28:51,231
Right.

488
00:28:53,192 --> 00:28:55,027
I like your necklace.

489
00:28:55,110 --> 00:28:56,153
Thanks.

490
00:28:56,195 --> 00:28:57,404
I've had it since I was 6.

491
00:28:57,487 --> 00:28:59,490
It's practically an antique.

492
00:29:00,991 --> 00:29:02,784
I like your boots.

493
00:29:02,868 --> 00:29:04,203
Thanks.

494
00:29:04,244 --> 00:29:06,246
I like your smile.

495
00:29:09,833 --> 00:29:13,504
Om.

496
00:29:14,046 --> 00:29:17,341
Om.

497
00:29:19,051 --> 00:29:20,802
Dinner, Mary, now.

498
00:29:20,886 --> 00:29:23,597
I'm on a hunger strike,
like Gandhi,

499
00:29:23,680 --> 00:29:24,890
driven to desperate measures

500
00:29:24,973 --> 00:29:27,100
by the insensitivity
of the British government.

501
00:29:27,184 --> 00:29:28,852
Not one morsel will pass my lips

502
00:29:28,936 --> 00:29:30,646
until you say
I can go see Sidarthur.

503
00:29:30,729 --> 00:29:32,648
You have got two minutes
to get to this table

504
00:29:32,731 --> 00:29:34,233
or the insensitive
British government

505
00:29:34,316 --> 00:29:35,943
is gonna take the door
off its hinges

506
00:29:36,026 --> 00:29:37,361
and drag you out here.

507
00:29:39,738 --> 00:29:40,447
Hello?

508
00:29:40,531 --> 00:29:43,534
Om.

509
00:29:43,575 --> 00:29:44,868
Come in if you must.

510
00:29:44,910 --> 00:29:46,161
Yeah.

511
00:29:46,245 --> 00:29:50,040
The thing is, the drama queen
has been Gandhi for two days.

512
00:29:50,082 --> 00:29:52,292
-I'll take her.
-Okay, I will try it.

513
00:29:52,376 --> 00:29:55,838
Your dad wants to know if
he can take you to the concert.

514
00:29:56,505 --> 00:29:58,298
