Borrowed it.
Sam borrowed it.

768
00:41:55,390 --> 00:41:57,100
It'll be back by Monday morning.

769
00:41:57,184 --> 00:41:58,936
Oh. Yeah.
I'm getting off.

770
00:41:58,977 --> 00:42:00,562
I can't go through with this.

771
00:42:00,646 --> 00:42:02,022
Ella, don't back out now.

772
00:42:02,105 --> 00:42:04,149
Please just let me have
one night of pure joy

773
00:42:04,233 --> 00:42:08,320
if I'm gonna have to spend the
rest of my youth behind bars.

774
00:42:08,654 --> 00:42:10,364
This better be
one great concert.

775
00:42:10,447 --> 00:42:11,824
That's a given.

776
00:42:11,865 --> 00:42:13,826
I don't want to
get near a scalper.

777
00:42:13,909 --> 00:42:15,327
You take the money, okay?

778
00:42:15,410 --> 00:42:16,829
Okay.

779
00:43:28,484 --> 00:43:31,153
Wow, you look beautiful.

780
00:43:31,236 --> 00:43:32,446
You too, Lola.

781
00:43:32,529 --> 00:43:33,197
Thanks.

782
00:43:33,280 --> 00:43:34,531
Yes, you do.

783
00:43:34,573 --> 00:43:35,949
Both of you.

784
00:43:36,033 --> 00:43:38,952
Now, the hotel is just
a few blocks from the theater.

785
00:43:39,036 --> 00:43:40,537
I know.
I know my New York.

786
00:43:40,621 --> 00:43:43,832
We'll be back
in the hotel room at 12:00.

787
00:43:43,916 --> 00:43:45,709
You have your tickets
and your money?

788
00:43:45,751 --> 00:43:46,710
We have the money.

789
00:43:46,752 --> 00:43:48,378
We'll buy the tickets.

790
00:43:48,420 --> 00:43:49,129
Oh, here.

791
00:43:49,213 --> 00:43:50,964
Thank you.

792
00:43:51,048 --> 00:43:52,424
We'll drop you off.

793
00:43:52,466 --> 00:43:55,177
I can assure you,
everything is gonna be fine.

794
00:43:55,260 --> 00:43:57,137
It's just a quiet
little concert.

795
00:44:12,861 --> 00:44:15,405
Okay, Ella, heads up.
March forward.

796
00:44:15,489 --> 00:44:17,407
-Get ready to rock 'n' roll.
-Girls, please.

797
00:44:17,449 --> 00:44:19,535
-Our tickets are at the door.
-Okay.

798
00:44:33,799 --> 00:44:35,425
Look for someone
who's selling tickets.

799
00:44:35,467 --> 00:44:37,219
Isn't there a stall
or something?

800
00:44:37,302 --> 00:44:40,764
No. They're just ordinary people
doing ordinary scalping.

801
00:44:41,306 --> 00:44:43,809
Watch this. You have to be
strict with these people.

802
00:44:43,892 --> 00:44:45,811
You have to bargain and deal.

803
00:44:45,894 --> 00:44:46,770
How much?

804
00:44:46,812 --> 00:44:49,064
$165 in orchestra.
Can't get any better than that.

805
00:44:49,147 --> 00:44:50,399
We'll take them.

806
00:44:50,482 --> 00:44:53,068
$165 doesn't leave us
very much for incidentals.

807
00:44:53,152 --> 00:44:56,572
When you get to see Stu Wolff,
you don't need incidentals.

808
00:44:56,905 --> 00:44:57,990
It's in your makeup bag.

809
00:44:58,073 --> 00:44:59,283
Oh, right.

810
00:45:03,495 --> 00:45:05,247
What's wrong?

811
00:45:06,206 --> 00:45:07,416
Ella, it's not here.

812
00:45:07,499 --> 00:45:09,459
My makeup bag's not here.

813
00:45:09,501 --> 00:45:10,460
It must be.

814
00:45:10,502 --> 00:45:12,421
It has to be.

815
00:45:12,504 --> 00:45:13,839
When did you last see it?

816
00:45:13,922 --> 00:45:14,840
In the train.

817
00:45:14,923 --> 00:45:18,510
I left it behind the sink.

818
00:45:18,844 --> 00:45:20,220
Oh, no.

819
00:45:20,929 --> 00:45:22,890
Oh.
Maybe it's karma.

820
00:45:22,973 --> 00:45:25,642
All we have to do is go in
with a large group of people.

821
00:45:25,726 --> 00:45:28,145
What?
You mean sneak in?

822
00:45:28,187 --> 00:45:29,563
Sneaking would be beneath us,

823
00:45:29,646 --> 00:45:33,567
but I can't think of a better
word for what we're about to do.

824
00:45:33,650 --> 00:45:35,903
I have never snuck ever.

825
00:45:35,986 --> 00:45:37,446
I can't do it.

826
00:45:37,529 --> 00:45:39,448
I'm terrified just being here.

827
00:45:39,531 --> 00:45:41,116
Stage fright.
It'll pass.

828
00:45:41,200 --> 00:45:44,077
This is a little tricky,
so just follow my lead, okay?

829
00:45:44,161 --> 00:45:45,579
I wonder what song they'll do.

830
00:45:45,662 --> 00:45:47,206
I hope they do "Love Loser."

831
00:45:47,289 --> 00:45:48,499
Oh, I'm so excited!

832
00:45:48,582 --> 00:45:51,043
I feel like I've been waiting
for this forever.

833
00:45:52,920 --> 00:45:54,379
Just a minute.

834
00:45:56,131 --> 00:45:58,550
Can I have another look
at your ticket, please?

835
00:46:00,052 --> 00:46:02,095
Right.
My ticket. Sure.

836
00:46:04,389 --> 00:46:06,141
You know, it's not here.

837
00:46:06,225 --> 00:46:08,185
I must have dropped it
or something.

838
00:46:09,686 --> 00:46:12,648
No ticket, no concert.

839
00:46:12,731 --> 00:46:14,525
I demand to see your supervisor.

840
00:46:14,566 --> 00:46:16,902
Yeah?
You can see him outside.

841
00:46:25,244 --> 00:46:27,246
Come to the door.

842
00:46:27,329 --> 00:46:30,916
Come to the door.

843
00:46:30,999 --> 00:46:33,001
Okay, go see Stu.

844
00:46:33,085 --> 00:46:35,337
Go see Stu.

845
00:46:35,420 --> 00:46:36,839
Go see Stu!

846
00:46:36,922 --> 00:46:37,840
Okay, stay there.

847
00:46:37,923 --> 00:46:39,883
Don't move.
I'm coming in.

848
00:46:39,925 --> 00:46:41,426
I just have to be
with my cousin.

849
00:46:41,510 --> 00:46:43,804
She has this rare disease
that makes you gag

850
00:46:43,887 --> 00:46:45,848
and you can't breathe
and then you die.

851
00:46:45,931 --> 00:46:47,266
She shouldn't be left alone.

852
00:46:47,307 --> 00:46:50,227
She's alone, the one who's
gagging and not breathing.

853
00:46:50,269 --> 00:46:52,896
I have to be with her
at all times.

854
00:46:53,605 --> 00:46:54,982
Okay.

855
00:46:58,777 --> 00:47:00,445
Good plan.

856
00:47:04,700 --> 00:47:06,618
Maybe we should just go
to the hotel.

857
00:47:06,702 --> 00:47:08,495
What?
And miss the concert?

858
00:47:08,579 --> 00:47:09,913
Yeah, I don't think so.

859
00:47:09,955 --> 00:47:11,748
We're not actually
at the concert.

860
00:47:11,832 --> 00:47:12,791
We're close.

861
00:47:12,833 --> 00:47:14,877
Stu Wolff's only
a few yards away from us.

862
00:47:14,960 --> 00:47:17,421
And then he'll be
at the after-party with us.

863
00:47:17,504 --> 00:47:19,631
Your belief system amazes me.

864
00:47:20,132 --> 00:47:22,593
Ella, where are you going?

865
00:47:22,634 --> 00:47:24,428
Don't leave me!

866
00:47:24,469 --> 00:47:26,555
Come back!
Ella!

867
00:47:26,638 --> 00:47:28,473
Ella, what are you doing?

868
00:47:28,557 --> 00:47:30,142
I'm going back to the hotel.

869
00:47:30,225 --> 00:47:31,852
So you're just gonna give up?

870
00:47:31,935 --> 00:47:33,437
What if everyone gave up, Ella?

871
00:47:33,520 --> 00:47:36,273
There'd be no America,
no electricity, no TiVo.

872
00:47:36,356 --> 00:47:38,901
We'd all have to watch our shows
at their scheduled times.

873
00:47:38,984 --> 00:47:41,278
We'd never get to see
the work of Renée Zellweger

874
00:47:41,320 --> 00:47:42,946
or Christina Aguilera.

875
00:47:43,030 --> 00:47:43,989
If everyone gave up,

876
00:47:44,072 --> 00:47:46,783
we'd all be sitting in mud huts
in Europe eating weeds.

877
00:47:46,825 --> 00:47:48,035
I didn't say stop progress.

878
00:47:48,118 --> 00:47:50,120
I just said,
"Go back to the hotel."

879
00:47:50,204 --> 00:47:52,206
Don't you want to see
the look on Carla's face

880
00:47:52,289 --> 00:47:53,999
when we show up at that party?

881
00:47:54,082 --> 00:47:55,876
Yeah, I do.

882
00:47:55,959 --> 00:47:57,628
Great!
Then let's go to Soho.

883
00:47:57,669 --> 00:47:58,795
Where in Soho?

884
00:47:58,837 --> 00:48:00,339
We don't even know
where Stu lives.

885
00:48:00,422 --> 00:48:03,467
Sure, we do.
I have this.

886
00:48:08,013 --> 00:48:09,389
A picture of a door?

887
00:48:09,473 --> 00:48:10,641
It's not just a door.

888
00:48:10,682 --> 00:48:13,101
It's a black door with windows.

889
00:48:13,185 --> 00:48:14,394
Have some faith, Ella.

890
00:48:14,478 --> 00:48:16,855
Soho is New York's
artistic soul.

891
00:48:16,939 --> 00:48:18,148
It's just around the corner.

892
00:48:33,038 --> 00:48:35,541
67 blocks is around the corner?

893
00:48:44,716 --> 00:48:46,468
-Ready?
-Yeah.

894
00:48:52,975 --> 00:48:54,351
Ready?

895
00:48:54,393 --> 00:48:56,061
Ohh.

896
00:49:24,131 --> 00:49:26,592
There's a man following us.

897
00:49:27,134 --> 00:49:28,135
Don't be silly, Ella.

898
00:49:28,218 --> 00:49:30,429
The crime rate in New York
is going down.

899
00:49:32,973 --> 00:49:34,516
Come on.
Let's go.

900
00:49:44,443 --> 00:49:46,945
There's a man
and a dog following us.

901
00:49:49,406 --> 00:49:51,283
Okay. Stay here.
I'll handle this.

902
00:49:51,366 --> 00:49:53,035
New Yorkers
know how to handle trouble.

903
00:49:53,118 --> 00:49:53,911
Watch this.

904
00:49:53,952 --> 00:49:55,537
Hey! Hey!

905
00:49:56,121 --> 00:49:58,457
-Dad, what are you doing here?
-Your mom called.

906
00:49:58,540 --> 00:50:00,417
Asked me to keep an eye on you.

907
00:50:00,751 --> 00:50:02,252
She got nervous.

908
00:50:02,336 --> 00:50:04,421
Mom was born nervous.

909
00:50:04,505 --> 00:50:06,465
So, where are you going?

910
00:50:06,507 --> 00:50:07,758
To a party.

911
00:50:07,799 --> 00:50:09,843
Not like that.
You're all wet.

912
00:50:09,927 --> 00:50:12,387
Daddy, nothing can rain
on my parade.

913
00:50:12,471 --> 00:50:13,514
I like parties.

914
00:50:13,597 --> 00:50:14,848
Please, Dad, if you show up,

915
00:50:14,932 --> 00:50:16,683
then Stu Wolff
will never think I'm cool.

916
00:50:16,767 --> 00:50:18,268
Can't you wait outside
or something?

917
00:50:18,352 --> 00:50:20,103
Right outside.

918
00:50:20,145 --> 00:50:23,190
But if I see something even
slightly wrong, I'm coming in.

919
00:50:23,273 --> 00:50:24,775
You know, I really like parties.

920
00:50:24,817 --> 00:50:25,984
Thanks, Dad.

921
00:50:26,068 --> 00:50:27,110
And could you lay low?

922
00:50:27,152 --> 00:50:29,279
You're scaring my friend.

923
00:50:30,113 --> 00:50:31,490
Right.

924
00:50:31,532 --> 00:50:33,116
But I'll be watching.

925
00:50:34,493 --> 00:50:36,286
Well, he won't be
bothering us anymore.

926
00:50:36,328 --> 00:50:37,955
So, are you ready to have fun?

927
00:50:38,038 --> 00:50:39,289
I hope so.

928
00:50:39,331 --> 00:50:40,666
Okay. Good.

929
00:50:50,175 --> 00:50:51,635
Yeah!

930
00:50:55,681 --> 00:50:57,766
That was the Santini car.

931
00:51:41,226 --> 00:51:43,312
Hi! Lola Steppe.
Ella Gerard.

932
00:51:43,395 --> 00:51:44,354
Nice to see you again.

933
00:51:44,438 --> 00:51:46,356
I have to see your invitations.

934
00:51:46,398 --> 00:51:47,524
Strange you should ask.

935
00:51:47,566 --> 00:51:49,485
We left them at the concert.

936
00:51:50,235 --> 00:51:51,945
Our names should be on the list.

937
00:51:57,284 --> 00:51:58,869
There they are.

938
00:51:59,411 --> 00:52:01,038
Dr. And Mrs. Lawrence?

939
00:52:01,121 --> 00:52:01,788
Yeah.

940
00:52:01,872 --> 00:52:04,166
My mom and my dad.
They couldn't make it.

941
00:52:04,249 --> 00:52:07,002
My mom has a rash,
and my dad's in surgery.

942
00:52:07,085 --> 00:52:09,213
I thought your name was Steppe.

943
00:52:09,880 --> 00:52:12,799
Could I just use your phone?
I have to call my parents.

944
00:52:12,883 --> 00:52:14,760
This is a private residence,
not Grand Central Station.

945
00:52:14,843 --> 00:52:16,512
Use a public phone.

946
00:52:18,305 --> 00:52:20,390
Whoa, whoa!

947
00:52:20,432 --> 00:52:21,767
Stu, this is your own party!

948
00:52:21,808 --> 00:52:23,727
It's your own party.

949
00:52:26,104 --> 00:52:28,482
You don't tell me
what to do anymore, Steve.

950
00:52:28,565 --> 00:52:29,942
Don't you remember?
It's over.

951
00:52:29,983 --> 00:52:32,236
Come inside before you
embarrass yourself.

952
00:52:32,277 --> 00:52:34,530
You touch me...

953
00:52:39,368 --> 00:52:40,369
Yeah, remember?

954
00:52:40,452 --> 00:52:43,539
He's been trouble
all over the world.

955
00:52:43,622 --> 00:52:45,791
Thank God he's not
our problem anymore.

956
00:52:45,874 --> 00:52:48,126
Steve! Steve!

957
00:52:48,210 --> 00:52:50,337
I love you.

958
00:52:50,420 --> 00:52:53,340
Wait, let me just talk to you
for one minute.

959
00:52:55,926 --> 00:52:57,678
Except for the garbage
and the cars,

960
00:52:57,761 --> 00:52:59,555
it's like following Heathcliff
on the moors.

961
00:52:59,638 --> 00:53:01,598
-Maybe we shouldn't.
-Would you please relax?

962
00:53:01,682 --> 00:53:03,934
I'd rather lose him
than lose my life.

963
00:53:03,976 --> 00:53:07,104
-Where do you think he's going?
-Someplace great.

964
00:53:15,320 --> 00:53:17,364
This for you is great?

965
00:53:17,447 --> 00:53:20,325
I'm getting really scared being
out here all alone, Lola.

966
00:53:20,367 --> 00:53:21,160
We're not alone.

967
00:53:21,243 --> 00:53:24,079
We're with an adult.

968
00:53:24,163 --> 00:53:26,415
Aside from the fact
that he isn't actually with us,

969
00:53:26,498 --> 00:53:27,916
he isn't actually an adult.

970
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:29,751
He's a rock star.

971
00:53:38,010 --> 00:53:39,261
Mr. Wolff?

972
00:53:39,344 --> 00:53:40,554
What?

973
00:53:40,637 --> 00:53:42,055
Come with me.

974
00:53:42,472 --> 00:53:44,141
Come on.
Help me get him out.

975
00:53:44,183 --> 00:53:45,642
Oh. Oh.

976
00:53:47,311 --> 00:53:49,396
He smells like
a backed-up drain.

977
00:53:49,480 --> 00:53:52,191
Ella, Ella, Ella.
I mean, see the beauty.

978
00:53:52,274 --> 00:53:54,526
Oh, my God.
He's crying.

979
00:53:54,610 --> 00:53:57,196
Do you believe how lucky we are?

980
00:53:57,279 --> 00:53:59,907
I almost hear them praying
that we don't sit near them.

981
00:53:59,990 --> 00:54:03,327
Quickly get him into a booth
before anyone smells him.

982
00:54:04,995 --> 00:54:06,371
Ah.

983
00:54:06,413 --> 00:54:07,664
Ohh.

984
00:54:08,874 --> 00:54:11,835
Everybody wants something
from me.

985
00:54:11,877 --> 00:54:13,670
You think I'm a regular guy.

986
00:54:13,754 --> 00:54:16,006
I'm not a regular guy.

987
00:54:16,089 --> 00:54:19,968
Do you think anybody
really knows who I am?

988
00:54:20,594 --> 00:54:23,430
I don't even know who I am.

989
00:54:24,556 --> 00:54:26,058
Once we get some coffee in him,

990
00:54:26,141 --> 00:54:27,809
he'll become the man
of truth, passion,

991
00:54:27,893 --> 00:54:29,895
and unflagging courage
I know him to be.

992
00:54:29,978 --> 00:54:31,396
So, what will it be?

993
00:54:31,438 --> 00:54:34,149
Do you think I have
any real friends?

994
00:54:34,233 --> 00:54:35,442
We'll just have coffee.

995
00:54:35,526 --> 00:54:37,110
Not me.

996
00:54:37,194 --> 00:54:40,697
I'll have a deluxe hamburger
platter, well-done,

997
00:54:40,781 --> 00:54:43,700
and a large side of onion rings.

998
00:54:43,742 --> 00:54:45,118
You could just give him coffee.

999
00:54:45,202 --> 00:54:48,080
He's not really up to a meal
right now.

1000
00:54:48,121 --> 00:54:51,625
I want
a deluxe hamburger platter.

1001
00:54:51,708 --> 00:54:53,710
Is that too difficult?

1002
00:54:53,794 --> 00:54:55,254
You two better keep him in line.

1003
00:54:55,295 --> 00:54:58,298
The boss won't stand
for any nonsense.

1004
00:54:59,925 --> 00:55:01,468
What do you want?

1005
00:55:01,552 --> 00:55:03,011
Autographs?
Money?

1006
00:55:03,095 --> 00:55:04,054
A record deal?

1007
00:55:04,137 --> 00:55:07,224
Hey, there, girls,
do you want something from me?

1008
00:55:07,307 --> 00:55:09,977
This is a poet
who lit your darkest days?

1009
00:55:10,060 --> 00:55:12,938
Didn't I tell you
he was a tortured soul?

1010
00:55:13,021 --> 00:55:15,399
Stu, do you have
any cash on you?

1011
00:55:15,440 --> 00:55:17,901
We sort of left ours
on the train.

1012
00:55:18,235 --> 00:55:19,736
I knew you wanted money.

1013
00:55:19,778 --> 00:55:20,904
Look.

1014
00:55:22,781 --> 00:55:23,907
Nothing.

1015
00:55:26,243 --> 00:55:28,620
That's not onion rings.

1016
00:55:29,079 --> 00:55:30,247
Can you believe this?

1017
00:55:30,330 --> 00:55:33,083
We're actually having coffee
with Stu Wolff.

1018
00:55:33,125 --> 00:55:36,003
I have so much to ask you
about your work.

1019
00:55:37,421 --> 00:55:38,839
It's impossible
to talk to someone

1020
00:55:38,922 --> 00:55:40,382
who's had that much to drink.

1021
00:55:40,465 --> 00:55:43,302
You know, you just don't
understand the artistic soul.

1022
00:55:43,385 --> 00:55:46,388
He drinks so much to numb
the intensity of his feelings.

1023
00:55:46,471 --> 00:55:48,807
All geniuses do, Ella.

1024
00:55:48,891 --> 00:55:51,435
I want onion rings.

1025
00:55:51,977 --> 00:55:53,937
This is a donut!

1026
00:55:56,315 --> 00:55:58,025
I want onion rings.

1027
00:55:58,108 --> 00:55:59,234
Now.

1028
00:56:00,777 --> 00:56:03,822
What is wrong with
the service around here?

1029
00:56:03,906 --> 00:56:05,616
Are we together?

1030
00:56:05,991 --> 00:56:07,576
Who are you?

1031
00:56:07,659 --> 00:56:10,245
The fates have sort of
brought us together.

1032
00:56:10,329 --> 00:56:12,664
-This is Ella.
-Ella what?

1033
00:56:12,998 --> 00:56:13,790
Ella Gerard.

1034
00:56:13,832 --> 00:56:16,627
58 Birch Hollow Road,
Dellwood, New Jersey.

1035
00:56:16,668 --> 00:56:19,421
201-555-0199.

1036
00:56:19,505 --> 00:56:21,632
My parents are staying
at the New York Hilton.

1037
00:56:21,673 --> 00:56:24,092
I don't want to worry them
by being incarcerated.

1038
00:56:24,176 --> 00:56:25,677
It's my mother's birthday.

1039
00:56:25,761 --> 00:56:27,221
I bought her a rug.

1040
00:56:27,304 --> 00:56:28,931
Be quiet, Mr. Wolff.

1041
00:56:29,014 --> 00:56:30,140
You?

1042
00:56:30,516 --> 00:56:31,475
Lola Steppe.

1043
00:56:31,517 --> 00:56:33,352
My father's name
is Calum Steppe.

1044
00:56:33,435 --> 00:56:35,479
Address is 512 Bleecker Street.

1045
00:56:35,562 --> 00:56:38,732
212-555-0125.

1046
00:56:39,107 --> 00:56:40,317
All right, the three of you,

1047
00:56:40,400 --> 00:56:42,903
sit over there
while I make some calls.

1048
00:56:43,237 --> 00:56:44,822
What's wrong with you?

1049
00:56:44,863 --> 00:56:46,657
Why did you lie like that
to the police?

1050
00:56:46,698 --> 00:56:49,201
They're gonna find out
that your father is dead.

1051
00:56:49,243 --> 00:56:50,202
What's going on?

1052
00:56:50,244 --> 00:56:52,246
-Who are you two?
-What's wrong with you?

1053
00:56:52,329 --> 00:56:54,706
You're not afraid of what
your parents are gonna say?

1054
00:56:54,748 --> 00:56:56,917
I'm resigned
to what life may bring,

1055
00:56:57,000 --> 00:56:59,670
but why did you give
a false address?

1056
00:56:59,711 --> 00:57:02,506
You know, Ella, I think
your true soul and spirit

1057
00:57:02,548 --> 00:57:04,049
are finally beginning to emerge.

1058
00:57:04,091 --> 00:57:05,425
Why did you lie?

1059
00:57:05,509 --> 00:57:06,510
I didn't lie.

1060
00:57:06,552 --> 00:57:08,262
My father does live
on Bleecker Street.

1061
00:57:08,345 --> 00:57:11,640
And he has a rent-controlled
apartment and a dog named Negus.

1062
00:57:11,723 --> 00:57:15,102
You told me your father died
in a motorcycle accident.

1063
00:57:15,185 --> 00:57:17,354
So I exaggerated a little.

1064
00:57:17,396 --> 00:57:18,522
A little?

1065
00:57:18,605 --> 00:57:21,233
Exaggerating a little is saying
you're a little taller.

1066
00:57:21,316 --> 00:57:23,527
Saying your father is dead
when he's not

1067
00:57:23,569 --> 00:57:25,237
is lying beyond comprehension.

1068
00:57:25,320 --> 00:57:26,613
Can we talk about this later?

1069
00:57:26,697 --> 00:57:28,323
We should tell Stu
what happened first.

1070
00:57:28,407 --> 00:57:29,741
You should tell me
what happened.

1071
00:57:29,825 --> 00:57:31,994
Why did you say
your father was dead?

1072
00:57:32,077 --> 00:57:33,203
He died?

1073
00:57:33,245 --> 00:57:34,788
When?

1074
00:57:34,872 --> 00:57:36,123
I had a reason.

1075
00:57:36,206 --> 00:57:37,833
And what was that?

1076
00:57:37,916 --> 00:57:38,542
The truth?

1077
00:57:38,584 --> 00:57:39,626
No, a lie will do.

1078
00:57:39,710 --> 00:57:40,669
Yes, the truth!

1079
00:57:40,752 --> 00:57:43,088
You do remember what that is,
don't you?

1080
00:57:43,130 --> 00:57:44,339
Were we in a diner?

1081
00:57:44,423 --> 00:57:46,425
I have an image of "Merry Xmas."

1082
00:57:46,508 --> 00:57:48,635
Just give me a moment.
I'd be happy to explain.

1083
00:57:48,719 --> 00:57:50,929
Right now I'm talking to her.

1084
00:57:51,013 --> 00:57:53,557
All right.
The total truth.

1085
00:57:54,766 --> 00:57:58,729
I lied because I wanted to make
myself seem more interesting.

1086
00:57:58,812 --> 00:58:00,731
More interesting?

1087
00:58:01,315 --> 00:58:04,568
We are 1,000 miles from home
in a New York police station

1088
00:58:04,610 --> 00:58:08,155
with a drunken rock star waiting
for your dead father to show up.

1089
00:58:08,238 --> 00:58:11,158
You want to be more interesting?
More interesting than what?

1090
00:58:11,241 --> 00:58:13,452
You know,
you just don't understand.

1091
00:58:13,535 --> 00:58:15,579
It was a new town
and a new school.

1092
00:58:15,621 --> 00:58:17,080
I understand.

1093
00:58:17,122 --> 00:58:18,916
And I lied for my mom.

1094
00:58:18,957 --> 00:58:20,584
I had to protect her
against suburbia.

1095
00:58:20,626 --> 00:58:21,919
Your parents didn't get her.

1096
00:58:21,960 --> 00:58:24,463
So you killed your father?

1097
00:58:25,506 --> 00:58:26,965
Ella!

1098
00:58:27,049 --> 00:58:30,093
I would appreciate it
if you would just stop talking.

1099
00:58:30,135 --> 00:58:31,803
Ella, come on.

1100
00:58:41,480 --> 00:58:43,148
What's going on?

1101
00:58:43,482 --> 00:58:44,441
Arrest that man!

1102
00:58:44,483 --> 00:58:45,442
He's a stalker.

1103
00:58:45,484 --> 00:58:46,652
Ella, Dad.
Dad, Ella.

1104
00:58:46,735 --> 00:58:48,278
Hi.
I'm Calum Steppe, her father.

1105
00:58:48,362 --> 00:58:49,321
What happened?

1106
00:58:49,363 --> 00:58:50,614
That's what I've been asking.

1107
00:58:50,697 --> 00:58:52,574
<i>As the night continued
to fall on the dark,</i>

1108
00:58:52,658 --> 00:58:54,284
<i>heartless streets
around the precinct,</i>

1109
00:58:54,326 --> 00:58:56,119
<i>the six of us gathered
around the sergeant,</i>

1110
00:58:56,203 --> 00:58:57,287
<i>and I told our tale.</i>

1111
00:58:57,371 --> 00:58:59,414
We were desperate to get
into this man's concert

1112
00:58:59,498 --> 00:59:02,376
because I consider him to be the
greatest poet since Shakespeare.

1113
00:59:02,459 --> 00:59:04,628
We lost our money,
and we couldn't pay a scalper.

1114
00:59:04,711 --> 00:59:06,421
Then we tried to crash his party

1115
00:59:06,505 --> 00:59:08,799
rather than have our dreams
forever denied.

1116
00:59:08,841 --> 00:59:10,133
When he stormed out of his loft,

1117
00:59:10,217 --> 00:59:12,469
we followed him to make sure
he didn't come into any harm.

1118
00:59:12,511 --> 00:59:13,804
I'm having memory flashes.

1119
00:59:13,846 --> 00:59:15,597
I was passed out
amongst the rubbish.

1120
00:59:15,681 --> 00:59:17,307
I believe they helped me.

1121
00:59:17,391 --> 00:59:20,978
I know I should be furious,
but it's too late for fury.

1122
00:59:21,061 --> 00:59:22,813
I'm just thankful
nothing worse happened.

1123
00:59:22,896 --> 00:59:25,274
He looks like the dog
in "The Dog Years."

1124
00:59:25,357 --> 00:59:27,276
He is the dog
in "The Dog Years."

1125
00:59:27,860 --> 00:59:29,820
He's the dog in "The Dog Years"?

1126
00:59:29,903 --> 00:59:31,655
My niece loves those books.

1127
00:59:31,697 --> 00:59:33,907
-You're famous!
-He's not as famous as you.

1128
00:59:33,991 --> 00:59:36,326
Molly's not gonna believe
I've actually met you.

1129
00:59:36,368 --> 00:59:38,620
Negus, right?

1130
00:59:38,704 --> 00:59:40,122
And Calum Steppe, right?

1131
00:59:40,205 --> 00:59:41,582
Right.

1132
00:59:41,665 --> 00:59:44,293
We checked your story,
and you're free to go.

1133
00:59:44,376 --> 00:59:46,587
-Excuse me, Mr. Wolff?
-Mm-hmm.

1134
00:59:46,670 --> 00:59:48,547
Can I have your autograph?

1135
00:59:48,589 --> 00:59:49,840
Oh, yeah, sure.

1136
00:59:49,882 --> 00:59:51,008
Sure.

1137
00:59:51,049 --> 00:59:54,428
To Sergeant Rose.

1138
00:59:54,511 --> 00:59:56,513
Stu Wolff.

1139
00:59:56,889 --> 00:59:58,724
Right, well,
now that that's settled,

1140
00:59:58,765 --> 01:00:02,311
would anyone like to come
to a party with me?

1141
01:00:02,394 --> 01:00:04,188
I would.

1142
01:00:14,031 --> 01:00:16,408
You can't stay mad
at me forever.

1143
01:00:16,742 --> 01:00:18,827
Forgive me, please?

1144
01:00:18,911 --> 01:00:20,871
I am in no way ready
to forgive you.

1145
01:00:20,913 --> 01:00:22,414
This is the party
of the century.

1146
01:00:22,498 --> 01:00:23,957
Don't you want to enjoy it?

1147
01:00:24,041 --> 01:00:26,335
I'm not really
in a partying mood.

1148
01:00:26,418 --> 01:00:28,045
Look, I'm sorry.

1149
01:00:28,128 --> 01:00:30,088
I really am.
I'm sorry.

1150
01:00:30,130 --> 01:00:32,174
You're just saying that
to save the evening.

1151
01:00:32,257 --> 01:00:33,300
No, I'm not.

1152
01:00:33,383 --> 01:00:36,303
I honestly don't know
what I'd do without you.

1153
01:00:36,720 --> 01:00:39,223
What's going on?
Why are you still out here?

1154
01:00:39,306 --> 01:00:41,892
We just don't feel like
going in right now.

1155
01:00:41,934 --> 01:00:43,560
Well, then.

1156
01:00:43,644 --> 01:00:46,146
Let me get you
back to the hotel.

1157
01:00:49,441 --> 01:00:52,444
Maybe we can just go in
for a little while.

1158
01:01:02,246 --> 01:01:03,413
Hi!

1159
01:01:04,790 --> 01:01:06,625
There you are!
All right.

1160
01:01:06,708 --> 01:01:09,461
Listen, how about we get
you guys something dry to wear?

1161
01:01:09,545 --> 01:01:13,257
I'll have those dresses cleaned
and sent over to your dad's,

1162
01:01:13,298 --> 01:01:14,883
who is brilliant, by the way.

1163
01:01:14,967 --> 01:01:17,135
I think he and l
are gonna be pals.

1164
01:01:17,219 --> 01:01:18,637
Yeah, I bought all his books.

1165
01:01:25,978 --> 01:01:27,855
Just upstairs.

1166
01:01:27,938 --> 01:01:29,523
I don't see her, do you?

1167
01:01:29,606 --> 01:01:30,315
No.

1168
01:01:33,152 --> 01:01:34,611
Can you believe this?

1169
01:01:34,653 --> 01:01:37,072
We're in his clothes.

1170
01:01:37,948 --> 01:01:40,409
And in his bedroom.

1171
01:01:41,160 --> 01:01:44,121
Come on, Ella.
Celebrate with me, please.

1172
01:01:47,958 --> 01:01:50,627
I want everything
to be okay between us.

1173
01:01:50,669 --> 01:01:52,379
And I do, too.

1174
01:01:53,714 --> 01:01:57,217
You have to promise that
you'll never lie to me again.

1175
01:01:57,301 --> 01:01:59,011
I do.
I promise.

1176
01:01:59,094 --> 01:02:01,305
I swear, Ella.
I do.

1177
01:02:02,014 --> 01:02:03,265
You promise?

1178
01:02:03,348 --> 01:02:04,808
I do.

1179
01:02:06,393 --> 01:02:07,394
Okay.

1180
01:02:08,437 --> 01:02:09,646
Okay, then.

1181
01:02:09,688 --> 01:02:11,482
Come on, we're in his room.

1182
01:02:11,940 --> 01:02:13,025
What do you want to do?

1183
01:02:13,108 --> 01:02:14,485
I don't know.

1184
01:02:56,527 --> 01:02:58,445
That is so gross.

1185
01:02:59,279 --> 01:03:00,531
Carla!

1186
01:03:00,614 --> 01:03:02,991
Hey, Carla!

1187
01:03:03,075 --> 01:03:05,452
We've been looking for you.

1188
01:03:07,412 --> 01:03:09,164
Did you see her face?

1189
01:03:09,248 --> 01:03:11,208
She looks really angry.

1190
01:03:11,291 --> 01:03:12,251
I know that look.

1191
01:03:12,292 --> 01:03:15,754
You know, life can be
so randomly beautiful.

1192
01:03:16,797 --> 01:03:18,841
<i>Come on, girls!</i>

1193
01:03:23,303 --> 01:03:24,179
Oh, my God!

1194
01:03:49,288 --> 01:03:50,914
My saviors.

1195
01:03:50,956 --> 01:03:52,791
Oh, my God.

1196
01:03:53,375 --> 01:03:54,877
Oh, it's Steve.

1197
01:03:54,960 --> 01:03:56,086
-It's Steve!
-Hang on.

1198
01:03:56,128 --> 01:03:57,796
Stu, I know you're really busy.

1199
01:03:57,880 --> 01:03:59,798
I was wondering
if I could talk to you.

1200
01:03:59,882 --> 01:04:01,925
Why not?
Be my guest.

1201
01:04:02,634 --> 01:04:04,553
I can't believe I met you.

1202
01:04:04,636 --> 01:04:07,014
I mean, I can't believe
I'm sitting here with the man

1203
01:04:07,097 --> 01:04:09,892
who wrote all those songs
that made my spirit soar.

1204
01:04:09,975 --> 01:04:11,477
What were you thinking
when you wrote

1205
01:04:11,560 --> 01:04:15,189
"behind some doors people
are waiting to sparkle"?

1206
01:04:16,523 --> 01:04:18,275
I have no idea.

1207
01:04:19,651 --> 01:04:21,737
But you wrote it.

1208
01:04:21,820 --> 01:04:24,531
Life's a little foggy,
a little soggy.

1209
01:04:25,365 --> 01:04:27,326
You know, that really
said something to me.

1210
01:04:27,409 --> 01:04:29,203
I'm sure to a hundred million
other girls,

1211
01:04:29,286 --> 01:04:31,205
but especially to me.

1212
01:04:31,788 --> 01:04:33,957
I'm happy to oblige a fan.

1213
01:04:33,999 --> 01:04:35,709
No.
I'm not just a fan.

1214
01:04:35,792 --> 01:04:38,170
I mean, I sat at your feet,
metaphorically.

1215
01:04:38,253 --> 01:04:40,172
When I listen to
"Always Morning,"

1216
01:04:40,214 --> 01:04:43,258
I wore a gray jacket because you
wore a gray jacket on the CD.

1217
01:04:43,342 --> 01:04:45,177
You wore gray
because it was ambiguous.

1218
01:04:45,260 --> 01:04:46,929
Am I right?

1219
01:04:47,012 --> 01:04:48,055
No.

1220
01:04:48,138 --> 01:04:49,389
I'm right.

1221
01:04:56,313 --> 01:04:58,899
You look disappointed.

1222
01:04:58,982 --> 01:05:00,776
Well, I am.

1223
01:05:00,859 --> 01:05:01,902
In me.

1224
01:05:01,985 --> 01:05:02,945
Yeah.

1225
01:05:03,028 --> 01:05:04,029
I mean, I still think

1226
01:05:04,112 --> 01:05:06,240
you're the greatest thing
since Shakespeare.

1227
01:05:06,323 --> 01:05:07,241
It's just too bad

1228
01:05:07,324 --> 01:05:10,494
I'll never be able to discuss
your poetry with you.

1229
01:05:10,577 --> 01:05:11,787
Why?

1230
01:05:11,870 --> 01:05:16,291
Because, Mr. Wolff,
you're a drunk.

1231
01:05:29,221 --> 01:05:32,724
I hope getting this thing back
is easier than getting it out.

1232
01:05:32,808 --> 01:05:34,101
Guess what!

1233
01:05:34,184 --> 01:05:35,227
I've been grounded.

1234
01:05:35,310 --> 01:05:38,021
Me too!
I'm so proud of you!

1235
01:05:39,398 --> 01:05:41,191
This is the day
I've been waiting for

1236
01:05:41,233 --> 01:05:43,735
since my first summer camp
when Carla told all the kids

1237
01:05:43,777 --> 01:05:46,530
that if they played with me,
they'd die.

1238
01:05:49,366 --> 01:05:50,284
She's smiling.

1239
01:05:50,367 --> 01:05:51,660
Oh, she's bluffing.

1240
01:05:53,453 --> 01:05:55,873
Well, look,
I gotta get to class.

1241
01:05:55,914 --> 01:05:57,541
Tell me how it goes.

1242
01:05:57,624 --> 01:05:59,877
Come on.
Let's watch her sink.

1243
01:06:00,627 --> 01:06:02,129
Yeah.

1244
01:06:02,212 --> 01:06:03,672
Yeah, this one.
Look at this one.

1245
01:06:03,755 --> 01:06:04,673
Hey, Carla.

1246
01:06:04,756 --> 01:06:05,924
Did you have fun?

1247
01:06:06,008 --> 01:06:08,135
Well, if it isn't
the great pretender.

1248
01:06:08,218 --> 01:06:10,721
Come to hear what
the Sidarthur party was like?

1249
01:06:10,804 --> 01:06:12,514
Why would we want to hear
what you have to say?

1250
01:06:12,598 --> 01:06:13,515
Ella and I were there.

1251
01:06:13,599 --> 01:06:15,893
Did you hear that?
She said they were there.

1252
01:06:15,934 --> 01:06:18,061
You know,
lying's not gonna help you.

1253
01:06:18,103 --> 01:06:20,564
Everybody already knows
that you didn't go.

1254
01:06:20,606 --> 01:06:22,065
Don't pretend you didn't see us.

1255
01:06:22,107 --> 01:06:23,150
I know you did.

1256
01:06:23,233 --> 01:06:24,985
It just so happens Ella
and I got in

1257
01:06:25,068 --> 01:06:26,528
because of Stu Wolff himself

1258
01:06:26,612 --> 01:06:28,238
after we practically
saved his life.

1259
01:06:28,280 --> 01:06:29,072
Tell them, Ella.

1260
01:06:29,114 --> 01:06:31,909
I don't have anything to prove,
nor do you.

1261
01:06:31,992 --> 01:06:34,661
Ella, this is no time
for your newfound personality.

1262
01:06:34,745 --> 01:06:38,040
Maybe you'd like to see some
pictures from the party, Lola.

1263
01:06:38,123 --> 01:06:39,708
I know how fond you are
of Stu Wolff,

1264
01:06:39,791 --> 01:06:41,418
and I got some great shots
of him.

1265
01:06:41,502 --> 01:06:43,253
We spent the whole night
with Stu.

1266
01:06:43,337 --> 01:06:46,381
On the night of his biggest
party, he left to be with you.

1267
01:06:46,465 --> 01:06:47,758
You're not gonna get away
with this.

1268
01:06:47,799 --> 01:06:49,593
We were at that party.
My dad was there.

1269
01:06:49,676 --> 01:06:51,220
He and Stu are gonna
get together.

1270
01:06:51,303 --> 01:06:52,596
What dad?

1271
01:06:52,638 --> 01:06:54,515
You don't have a dad.

1272
01:06:54,598 --> 01:06:57,100
You said he died
before you moved here.

1273
01:06:57,184 --> 01:06:58,435
I mean, what do you do?

1274
01:06:58,477 --> 01:07:00,771
Do you just make all this up
as you go along?

1275
01:07:00,854 --> 01:07:04,024
Do you think because we're not
from New York that we're stupid?

1276
01:07:04,107 --> 01:07:05,025
You saw us there.

1277
01:07:05,108 --> 01:07:06,693
No, I didn't, liar.

1278
01:07:06,777 --> 01:07:09,446
You know, that's what you are.
You're a liar.

1279
01:07:09,488 --> 01:07:12,950
Your name isn't even Lola, Mary.

1280
01:07:13,992 --> 01:07:15,536
Ella's right.

1281
01:07:15,869 --> 01:07:18,330
I don't have to prove anything
to you people.

1282
01:07:18,413 --> 01:07:20,499
You know we were there.

1283
01:07:20,999 --> 01:07:22,709
Oh, no!
She's crying.

1284
01:07:22,793 --> 01:07:24,294
Look at the baby.

1285
01:07:24,378 --> 01:07:25,587
Oh.

1286
01:07:30,342 --> 01:07:32,678
Yo, you got no right to write
down what I'm saying.

1287
01:07:32,719 --> 01:07:34,054
Those are my --

1288
01:07:36,306 --> 01:07:38,934
I'm sorry, Miss Baggoli,
I can't go on.

1289
01:07:39,017 --> 01:07:40,394
There's something I have to say.

1290
01:07:40,477 --> 01:07:41,979
Well, quickly, Lola.
Quickly.

1291
01:07:42,020 --> 01:07:44,273
I have a confession to make.

1292
01:07:44,356 --> 01:07:46,900
I borrowed Eliza's dress
for the weekend.

1293
01:07:46,984 --> 01:07:49,862
I'm really sorry, but I felt
I had no other choice.

1294
01:07:49,945 --> 01:07:51,405
No choice?

1295
01:07:51,488 --> 01:07:52,698
Why?

1296
01:07:52,781 --> 01:07:54,825
I had to wear it
to the Sidarthur party.

1297
01:07:54,908 --> 01:07:57,411
When are you gonna
give it up, Mary?

1298
01:07:58,036 --> 01:07:59,037
No, you didn't.

1299
01:07:59,121 --> 01:08:00,581
You couldn't
have taken that dress

1300
01:08:00,664 --> 01:08:05,502
because I keep that dress locked
up safe in the drama room.

1301
01:08:05,544 --> 01:08:08,005
There are ways, Miss Baggoli.
There are ways.

1302
01:08:08,046 --> 01:08:09,756
Where is it now?

1303
01:08:09,840 --> 01:08:12,134
It's right back.
It's safe and sound.

1304
01:08:12,217 --> 01:08:14,678
It looks exactly the same,
but somehow different.

1305
01:08:14,761 --> 01:08:16,263
Can you believe her?

1306
01:08:16,346 --> 01:08:17,973
I mean, first,
she takes the dress.

1307
01:08:18,056 --> 01:08:19,349
Then, she puts it back.

1308
01:08:19,391 --> 01:08:22,019
And then she goes to this party
where no one saw her.

1309
01:08:22,102 --> 01:08:23,770
It's true!
The dress got all wet.

1310
01:08:23,854 --> 01:08:25,814
Stu Wolff made me change
into something dry.

1311
01:08:25,898 --> 01:08:27,858
He said it was important
that I felt comfortable.

1312
01:08:27,941 --> 01:08:30,027
Because on the night
of his farewell concert,

1313
01:08:30,068 --> 01:08:33,447
Stu Wolff had nothing better
to do than see Mary Steppe dry.

1314
01:08:33,530 --> 01:08:34,490
Girls, please!

1315
01:08:34,573 --> 01:08:37,367
He sent it back to my dad in a
limousine as big as this stage.

1316
01:08:37,451 --> 01:08:38,827
A dress in a limousine.

1317
01:08:38,911 --> 01:08:40,329
Can you picture it?

1318
01:08:40,412 --> 01:08:43,290
He's also a big fan
of my dad and my dad's dog.

1319
01:08:43,373 --> 01:08:45,334
Then your dog gave him
his autograph, right?

1320
01:08:45,417 --> 01:08:47,836
But I did take the dress!

1321
01:08:47,920 --> 01:08:50,631
See, Stu Wolff gave me this
himself.

1322
01:08:52,841 --> 01:08:55,677
It's his T-shirt from his tour.
Where would I have gotten it?

1323
01:08:55,761 --> 01:08:57,721
In a junk store
where you get everything else.

1324
01:08:57,805 --> 01:09:00,307
But this is the tissue I used
to wipe his tears.

1325
01:09:00,390 --> 01:09:02,768
Maybe we should send it off
for DNA testing.

1326
01:09:02,810 --> 01:09:04,770
I left my bottle-cap necklace
at his house.

1327
01:09:04,853 --> 01:09:06,647
He told my dad
he's gonna Fed-Ex it back.

1328
01:09:06,730 --> 01:09:09,399
A dress riding in a limousine.

1329
01:09:09,441 --> 01:09:10,609
I guess that's a good thing

1330
01:09:10,692 --> 01:09:13,904
because otherwise it would
have had to catch a cab.

1331
01:09:14,488 --> 01:09:16,698
You're funny, Lola.
You could be a comedienne.

1332
01:09:16,782 --> 01:09:20,410
But can we please
go back to work now?

1333
01:09:20,494 --> 01:09:23,455
We have so much to do
before Wednesday night.

1334
01:09:23,497 --> 01:09:24,748
You believe me, don't you?

1335
01:09:24,832 --> 01:09:26,208
Carla's the one who's lying.

1336
01:09:26,291 --> 01:09:30,128
We've worked so hard
for this production, Lola.

1337
01:09:30,212 --> 01:09:36,134
And I am not gonna let you
ruin it for me.

1338
01:09:39,471 --> 01:09:43,100
We have all had enough.

1339
01:09:43,976 --> 01:09:45,477
Have you?

1340
01:09:45,561 --> 01:09:48,272
Have you finally had enough?

1341
01:10:11,253 --> 01:10:14,673
<i>I sunk into a depression that
only Hamlet would recognize.</i>

1342
01:10:14,715 --> 01:10:17,593
<i>The one story I'd told that was
both probable and possible</i>

1343
01:10:17,676 --> 01:10:19,344
<i>was the one that was true.</i>

1344
01:10:19,428 --> 01:10:21,472
<i>And yet no one believed me.</i>

1345
01:10:21,805 --> 01:10:22,931
<i>Maybe you can never win</i>

1346
01:10:23,015 --> 01:10:25,642
<i>against the Carla Santinis
of this world.</i>

1347
01:10:25,684 --> 01:10:28,187
<i>I'd never felt
so totally defeated.</i>

1348
01:10:28,228 --> 01:10:30,981
<i>I felt more like a pigeon
than a flamingo.</i>

1349
01:10:31,565 --> 01:10:33,484
Mary?
Ella's here.

1350
01:10:33,525 --> 01:10:34,902
Go ahead.

1351
01:10:37,154 --> 01:10:38,405
I want to talk to you.

1352
01:10:38,489 --> 01:10:39,907
I don't really feel too well.

1353
01:10:39,990 --> 01:10:41,074
You can cut the crap.

1354
01:10:41,158 --> 01:10:42,701
I know what you're doing.

1355
01:10:42,784 --> 01:10:46,830
What happened to the most polite
girl in all of New Jersey?

1356
01:10:46,914 --> 01:10:50,083
What does it matter anymore?
We know we went to the party.

1357
01:10:50,167 --> 01:10:53,170
We know who we met
and what we did.

1358
01:10:54,213 --> 01:10:55,130
Get up!

1359
01:10:56,089 --> 01:10:57,049
I can't.

1360
01:10:57,090 --> 01:10:58,550
I just can't.

1361
01:10:59,885 --> 01:11:02,596
Has anyone seen Lola Steppe?

1362
01:11:03,305 --> 01:11:05,974
Has anyone seen Lola Steppe?
Lola?

1363
01:11:06,058 --> 01:11:07,476
You know, I really am sick.

1364
01:11:07,559 --> 01:11:08,519
I mean, ask my mom.

1365
01:11:08,602 --> 01:11:09,645
I'm not buying it.

1366
01:11:09,728 --> 01:11:11,188
You're bailing out of the play.

1367
01:11:11,271 --> 01:11:14,691
You know, here I am, so sick
this could turn into pneumonia,

1368
01:11:14,733 --> 01:11:17,611
and then I'll be on my deathbed,
and you're being accusatory.

1369
01:11:17,694 --> 01:11:19,947
You can't do this, Lola.

1370
01:11:20,030 --> 01:11:21,323
Everyone is depending on you.

1371
01:11:21,406 --> 01:11:23,575
What about your parents and Sam?

1372
01:11:23,659 --> 01:11:26,078
Sam has never been to
a school function in his life.

1373
01:11:26,119 --> 01:11:28,205
He's only going because of you.

1374
01:11:28,956 --> 01:11:29,957
Lola!

1375
01:11:30,040 --> 01:11:31,834
Lola Steppe, my Eliza.

1376
01:11:31,917 --> 01:11:33,544
Get out of my way.

1377
01:11:34,253 --> 01:11:36,547
One hour till curtain.

1378
01:11:39,341 --> 01:11:41,051
What about me?

1379
01:11:43,095 --> 01:11:47,099
I was miserable
until you came to Dellwood.

1380
01:11:47,182 --> 01:11:49,601
I thought everyone's life
was like mine.

1381
01:11:49,643 --> 01:11:51,311
Doing everything
you're supposed to do

1382
01:11:51,395 --> 01:11:53,313
when you're supposed to do it.

1383
01:11:53,814 --> 01:11:56,275
Never questioning anything.

1384
01:11:58,485 --> 01:12:00,946
The only thing I could expect
when I grew up

1385
01:12:01,029 --> 01:12:03,949
was a life like my parents'.

1386
01:12:05,033 --> 01:12:07,995
And then I met you.

1387
01:12:09,913 --> 01:12:12,666
You gave me courage, Lola.

1388
01:12:15,002 --> 01:12:18,422
Because of you, I'm brave enough
to be different.

1389
01:12:20,632 --> 01:12:22,759
Don't touch me!

1390
01:12:23,343 --> 01:12:25,095
You're a sham!

1391
01:12:25,971 --> 01:12:28,599
The one thing Carla
can't do anything about

1392
01:12:28,682 --> 01:12:30,017
is you being Eliza Doolittle.

1393
01:12:30,100 --> 01:12:32,269
You're just gonna
hand it to her.

1394
01:12:36,190 --> 01:12:37,608
Mary, I left word with your dad.

1395
01:12:37,649 --> 01:12:40,194
Should I call Miss Baggoli?

1396
01:12:46,283 --> 01:12:47,659
No.

1397
01:12:47,701 --> 01:12:50,287
I've had a miraculous recovery.

1398
01:13:00,797 --> 01:13:02,090
I need to be sure.

1399
01:13:02,174 --> 01:13:03,217
Are you up to this?

1400
01:13:03,300 --> 01:13:05,636
Up to it? Miss Baggoli,
I was born to play Eliza.

1401
01:13:05,677 --> 01:13:07,596
Get into costume
for the opening.

1402
01:13:07,679 --> 01:13:08,972
Knock 'em dead!

1403
01:13:09,014 --> 01:13:10,516
Knock 'em dead!

1404
01:13:11,642 --> 01:13:14,520
It even amazes me that I get
everything that I want.

1405
01:13:17,523 --> 01:13:18,482
Get out of my dress.

1406
01:13:18,524 --> 01:13:20,818
-As of right now, I'm Eliza.
-Get out of my dress!

1407
01:13:20,901 --> 01:13:23,362
-Enjoy the show.
-Thanks. I will.

1408
01:13:23,403 --> 01:13:25,113
Oh, and get out
of my first costume!

1409
01:13:25,197 --> 01:13:26,990
Five minutes till curtain,
people.

1410
01:13:27,074 --> 01:13:28,492
Five minutes.

1411
01:13:31,537 --> 01:13:32,746
Get out of my dress.

1412
01:13:32,830 --> 01:13:33,497
No!

1413
01:13:33,539 --> 01:13:34,915
Get out of my dress!

1414
01:13:34,998 --> 01:13:36,917
-No!
-Get out of that dress!

1415
01:13:37,000 --> 01:13:38,460
Ohh!

1416
01:13:39,378 --> 01:13:41,338
Sorry, Miss Baggoli.

1417
01:13:41,380 --> 01:13:42,798
I'm so glad to see you.

1418
01:13:46,051 --> 01:13:48,220
Do you want an ice cream?

1419
01:13:50,347 --> 01:13:51,431
Hey.

1420
01:13:51,515 --> 01:13:53,183
You're gonna be great.

1421
01:13:54,101 --> 01:13:55,686
I'm scared.
I'll admit it.

1422
01:13:55,727 --> 01:13:57,146
But I'm excited, too.

1423
01:13:57,229 --> 01:13:59,690
Don't be afraid.

1424
01:14:00,274 --> 01:14:02,234
You're gonna be wonderful, Lola.

1425
01:14:06,488 --> 01:14:08,782
You called me Lola.

1426
01:14:08,866 --> 01:14:10,868
You are a Lola.

1427
01:14:10,909 --> 01:14:12,161
Good luck!

1428
01:14:48,947 --> 01:14:51,575
Press your bars, children.

1429
01:15:12,679 --> 01:15:14,765
Yo, you gots no rights
to write down what I'm saying.

1430
01:15:14,848 --> 01:15:16,850
Those are my personal words.

1431
01:16:04,606 --> 01:16:06,316
Now say "New York."

1432
01:16:06,400 --> 01:16:07,901
New Yolk.

1433
01:16:07,985 --> 01:16:09,444
New York.

1434
01:16:09,528 --> 01:16:11,029
With an "R."

1435
01:16:11,071 --> 01:16:12,573
New Rolk.

1436
01:16:14,533 --> 01:16:15,909
You can't talk.

1437
01:16:15,993 --> 01:16:18,036
Let's see if you can walk.

1438
01:16:18,120 --> 01:16:19,830
Ugh!

1439
01:16:54,781 --> 01:16:57,493
They all accepted her
because of me.

1440
01:16:57,576 --> 01:16:59,328
All because of you?

1441
01:16:59,411 --> 01:17:01,205
I was there, too!

1442
01:17:01,288 --> 01:17:03,874
I worked hard to make you
look good!

1443
01:17:03,916 --> 01:17:06,210
Well, what will you
do now, dear?

1444
01:17:10,964 --> 01:17:12,841
I will be a teacher

1445
01:17:12,925 --> 01:17:15,302
because being a teacher
is the most worthy thing

1446
01:17:15,385 --> 01:17:17,137
a person can be.

1447
01:17:51,672 --> 01:17:53,006
Bravo!

1448
01:19:39,071 --> 01:19:41,073
Stu Wolff?

1449
01:19:41,532 --> 01:19:45,410
I don't believe this.

1450
01:19:46,328 --> 01:19:49,873
Did my father invite you here?

1451
01:19:50,541 --> 01:19:51,917
No.

1452
01:19:52,543 --> 01:19:53,627
May I come in anyway?

1453
01:19:53,710 --> 01:19:54,628
Yes!

1454
01:19:54,711 --> 01:19:56,296
Yeah, sure, of course.

1455
01:19:56,380 --> 01:19:58,382
I don't believe this.
This is crazy.

1456
01:19:58,423 --> 01:20:01,051
Lola's father said
she would be here.

1457
01:20:01,718 --> 01:20:04,888
You're here in my house
because of Lola?

1458
01:20:05,764 --> 01:20:07,432
You know what?
Why don't you stay here?

1459
01:20:07,516 --> 01:20:09,852
You stay.
And I'm gonna go get her.

1460
01:20:09,935 --> 01:20:11,562
And I'm gonna go get her.

1461
01:20:11,645 --> 01:20:12,688
You stay.

1462
01:20:12,771 --> 01:20:14,898
So I can't come in?

1463
01:20:24,032 --> 01:20:25,993
Look who came to see me.

1464
01:20:27,786 --> 01:20:28,745
Hey, guys.

1465
01:20:28,787 --> 01:20:30,289
Look who's here.

1466
01:20:30,372 --> 01:20:32,291
Is that Stu Wolff?

1467
01:20:32,624 --> 01:20:34,835
Look who came to my house.

1468
01:20:40,966 --> 01:20:43,427
Hey, Ella.
I just wanted to say --

1469
01:20:43,969 --> 01:20:45,179
Lola!

1470
01:20:51,018 --> 01:20:53,479
You left this at my place.

1471
01:21:12,039 --> 01:21:16,168
<i>I had pictured this moment
in my craziest, wildest dreams.</i>

1472
01:21:18,170 --> 01:21:20,088
<i>I guess if you don't dream
crazy and wild,</i>

1473
01:21:20,172 --> 01:21:23,801
<i>people like Stu Wolff don't
return your jewelry personally.</i>

1474
01:21:28,806 --> 01:21:29,598
Aah!

1475
01:21:44,655 --> 01:21:46,907
Come on.
It's just a hand.

1476
01:22:07,678 --> 01:22:09,346
Thanks for showing up.

1477
01:22:10,013 --> 01:22:11,849
So, how have you been?

1478
01:22:11,890 --> 01:22:13,100
Sober.

1479
01:22:13,183 --> 01:22:14,726
I'm in recovery.

1480
01:22:14,810 --> 01:22:15,811
Again.

1481
01:22:17,604 --> 01:22:22,776
Someone very sweet told me I was
a drunk, and I didn't like it.

1482
01:22:22,860 --> 01:22:24,736
Sounds kind of harsh.

1483
01:22:25,445 --> 01:22:26,864
But it woke me up.

1484
01:22:28,240 --> 01:22:31,869
So, maybe sometime soon we can
talk about your amazing music.

1485
01:22:31,910 --> 01:22:33,537
Just say when.

1486
01:22:33,579 --> 01:22:35,080
I can say when?

1487
01:22:35,122 --> 01:22:37,040
Within reason.

1488
01:22:41,086 --> 01:22:43,213
Would you like to dance?

1489
01:22:43,589 --> 01:22:44,798
Absolutely.

1490
01:23:02,483 --> 01:23:03,817
<i>Here's what I learned.</i>

1491
01:23:03,942 --> 01:23:06,653
<i>When you're happy,
the whole world's New York.</i>

1492
01:23:06,737 --> 01:23:08,864
<i>And that dreams are important.</i>

1493
01:23:08,947 --> 01:23:12,951
<i>Someday, when you're not
even looking, they find you.</i>

1494
01:23:15,954 --> 01:23:17,831
<i>And then there's Sam.</i>

1495
01:23:17,915 --> 01:23:19,124
<i>He'd been there all along,</i>

1496
01:23:19,208 --> 01:23:21,627
<i>but when I opened my heart
to him, I thought,</i>

1497
01:23:21,668 --> 01:23:25,088
<i>now that my career is launched,
maybe I could have a boyfriend.</i>

1498
01:23:43,649 --> 01:23:45,108
<i>It was the first time
I realized</i>

1499
01:23:45,192 --> 01:23:49,154
<i>that absolute reality could be
so much more fun than fantasy.</i>

1500
01:23:50,948 --> 01:23:53,200
<i>And can you believe
all of this happened</i>

1501
01:23:53,283 --> 01:23:57,120
<i>in Dellwood, New Jersey,
of all places?</i>

